animal.description:
DOB: 1/2014 Weight: 48 lbs

Ok....will you look at this mug? Buster attended his first adoption event and everyone clearly fell in love with him. Grumpy face and all, this boy seems to be just the sweetest. He was surrendered when his family moved and decided not to bring him with them. Maybe that's why the grumpy face? He can be very picky sometimes with other dogs, so we think he would do best in a home without them. He also did not test well with cats so would need to go to a home without them as well. Buster also did great with our younger volunteers, but maybe shouldn't be in a home with really young kids (12 and under) as he seems to be more comfortable around older, more considerate ones. Please help us find this sweet boy a soul mate because after all, happiness is a loving home! If you would like to foster or try our two week foster to adopt program, go to pcpoundpuppies.com to fill out an application. Buster has a sponsor. His $150 sponsorship will be used to send him to his new home with a bag of good food picked out especially for him, plus flea and heartworm preventative for the first few months. He will get a good start on a new life thanks to the generosity of his sponsor! ***Buster is on urinary food to help his kidneys. It's about $100 a month. He also needs routine bloodwork to make sure the food is doing its job.

Buster is neutered, up to date on shots, microchipped and heartworm tested negative. He came to the shelter 12/2017.***YOU MUST FILL OUT AN APPLICATION BEFORE WE DO ANY MEET AND GREETS. QUESTIONS? CONTACT pcpoundpuppies1@gmail.com
Our adoption fee is $150 which covers a portion of the dog's vetting costs. The adoption process includes the completion of an application followed by an interview.
Click here to submit an adoption application: https://pcpoundpuppies.webs.com/adoption-application
***IMPORTANT: Due to the effects of COVID-19, our Sunday adoption events at Pet Food Center have been canceled until further notice. If there is a dog you are interested in meeting, be sure to contact us and we may be able to set up a meet and greet as soon as possible.***
You can get in touch with us by email at pcpoundpuppies1@gmail.com or by phone at 812-483-4341 for more information.
We respond to inquiries and adoption applications at our earliest opportunity, but please be patient with us as we work full-time jobs and perform this service as volunteers. We do our best to return messages and schedule adoption interviews within a couple of days of receiving your application.
The fastest way to get the ball rolling is to complete an adoption application for the dog that caught your eye. Thank you for considering the adoption of a shelter dog!

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in Churchill. He is about 7 years old. We transferred him into our shelter about 2.5 years ago from a municipal shelter in central NC. He was heartworm positive when we got him but that has been treated and he has been on preventative since. He also had a large tumor on his chest in which we had removed, it did come back as cancerous but all scans since have been clear. Churchill is very calm and laid back and walks great on a leash. He never uses the bathroom in his kennel here at the shelter. He is not a barker at all. In fact I have only heard him bark a few times and this was when other dogs were running the fence beside him. He loves all of our staff and volunteers but it can sometimes take him a bit to warm up to strangers. He must go to a home with no other pets and no children as he is not fond of either. Churchills adoption fee is $50. 

If you are interested in scheduling a meet and greet with this pet please use the following link to submit an adoption application. Once we have received and reviewed this we will contact you either by phone or email to set up an appointment. If you have any further questions about this pet or our adoption process please give the shelter a call at (828)743-5752.

https://chhumanesociety.org/adopt/adoption-application

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!Well hey there guys. My name is Charles and I LOVE my humans!!! I like dogs too but I just can't get close enough to a human they are AMAZING!!!I had surgery to fix my knee and I have 1 more week of crate rest and then I will be ready to get back in my humans lap and sleep in bed etc... If you want a dog who will be your little shadow and HATES to be alone then I am your man!!!PS my one ear is bent down but my mom says that just makes me even more special! I stand out in a crowd :)Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

I will ONLY be adopted WITH Laverne

Foster Homes Needed!

Do you have time and room in your life for a foster dog?

http://www.muttloverescue.org/foster.html

*****************

Hi,

My name is Sam and I'm looking for my new forever home, do you have room in your hearts and home? I'm a very smart girl, my foster mom tells me all the time, she also thinks I'm funny. The attached video and pictures should show that quality in me. I'm very well trained, and my manners are impeccable. I love to snuggle on the couch and watch TV with you, if it's Animal Planet I may even become more interested in what you're watching. I like to go on walks, but not too long, I like my couch, or if you don't like me on the furniture a nice plush dog bed will do. I do have some fear so I am looking for a forever family that has no small children, and a confident owner that has experience and patience when I become fearful. Please inquire about me, I don't think you'll be disappointed. My foster mom has helped me feel better, will you?

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

For information on sponsoring this dog, please write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

WE NEED FOSTER HOMES! FOR MORE INFORMATION, PLEASE EMAIL ADOPT@MUTTLOVERESCUE.ORG.

animal.description:
Pork Chop is my name and LOVE is my game!!! 
I am a super sweet gorgeous girl that was rescued all the way from Puerto Rico!!
Did you know that they poison dogs that are on the streets in Puerto Rico? So I was one of the lucky ones to make it out!! 
I am around 2 years old and I just LOVE people!! I would  love to cuddle next to you and keep you company while you watch TV or read the paper.... and maybe sneak in a few kisses too!! 
I love to play ball and tug of war.  Sometimes the volunteers catch me playing a game of fetch with my own self!! As you can see by my video... I just LOVE belly rubs and attention and hanging out and having fun with my people. I am a loving, silly, playful goofball all rolled into one great little package! 
I could use a little help with my basic training.... but I am a smart girl, so I am sure I will learn quickly with a little time and patience!! 
I love people so much and get so excited to meet them, that I tend to jump up on them to say Hello!  So it would be best if I go to a home with older children.  I pull a bit on leash... but a harness would likely work wonders!!! 
Pork Chop had a meet and greet with another doggie friend at the rescue and did great!!! She can be dog selective so proper introductions are required and always recommended for any dog. They are not sure if I have ever been around those little furry things you all call cats!! 
So.... if you think you could be that special someone that would like to give a love bug like me a new home..... please fill out an adoption application at: 
                               www.dawghous.com
I am totally worth it!!!!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Hello Gorgeous! We believe Daisy is a Great Pyrenees/Golden Retriever, with the size (100+ lbs) and guardian instincts of a Pyrenees. She has very good manners in the house, but prefers a quiet home without too many visitors. She enjoys daily walks and generally does well meeting most dogs on her walks. Daisy is not always happy about meeting new people -- she isn't aggressive, but she doesn't trust easily. She has a scary bark and uses it to keep people from encroaching on her personal space. She tends to accept people more easily if they have a dog, and the second time she sees them, she may basically ignore them. People who love dogs and think that most dogs love them back are often surprised that Daisy won't let them pet her. But she is a one-family dog. Once you earn her trust, she rewards you with complete devotion, and will be very affectionate with you.

Daisy currently lives in a foster home with several dogs, some her own size and some much smaller. She gets along with all of them, though will often find a quiet spot away from the others to take her nap. She previously lived in a foster home with a small dog and a senior cat, and everyone got along just fine.

If you live a nice quiet life and would give to Daisy the same love and devotion she will give to you, Daisy just may be the dog for you!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Emmy Lou is such a beautiful girl that it's no surprise she had the misfortune of being used by a backyard breeder, forced to produce one litter after another for the first few years of her life. When the guy decided he needed "new blood" in his breeding line, he dumped Emmy at the closest shelter.
We were happy to bring her to Windsong Ranch and introduce her to a better life.

Emmy Lou has an estimated birthday in June 2010, but in spite of her age, she appears to be in great health. She is slow to adapt to change, and her adopter will need to be someone who is committed to taking the time necessary for her to become accustomed to new surroundings. We know from observing her behavior here that she really appreciates having the opportunity to spend a lot of time outside, under a shade tree, watching over her domain, but she prefers to sleep inside the house.

Emmy Lou gets along just fine with other dogs, but we believe she would be happiest in a home where either she's the only dog, or where there might be only one other dog, so she can continue to get the attention she has learned to love. She is safe with livestock, including chickens, so she could be a good addition to a farm or small homestead, but she is NOT a livestock guardian. She is a companion dog -- a pet who will enrich your life with her love and devotion, whose presence may keep predators away, but who really doesn't want to spend the rest of her life in the pasture.

If Emmy Lou sounds like a girl after your own heart, and if you have the patience to love her even as she's trying to decide whether she likes you, please complete an application on our website: https://www.bluebonnetrescue.org/info/adoption.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Lindsey was pregnant when she was picked up by animal control in a small East Texas town. She delivered 10 pups in the shelter, but one did not survive. It's really a testament to the care that shelter staff and volunteers provided that they lost only one, as a shelter is no place for newborn puppies. The shelter posted this precious family, looking for a rescue to take them. Great Pyrenees rescues across Texas turned them down because they are obviously mixes, and the rescues were already jam-packed with dogs and pups who looked more like Pyrs. Shelter staff had no choice but to add Lindsey and all her puppies to their list for euthanasia, which would have been a sad day for everyone. Thankfully, one of our foster moms volunteered to foster the whole family, and we were happy to take them into Bluebonnet Animal Rescue. We love our Great Pyrs, but we are not limited to just one breed, so it didn't matter to us that they are mixes.

We think Lindsey is a Great Pyrenees/Border Collie mix. She's friendly and playful, and loves people. Lindsey has been spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped. She gets along well with other dogs, but can be a little bit alpha in her behavior. She enjoys taking a dip in the wading pool to cool off in summer. Lindsey has a high prey drive and is NOT safe with livestock or cats.

If you have room in your heart and home for this beautiful girl, please read about our process and submit your application on our website: https://www.bluebonnetrescue.org/info/adoption.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Bobby's mom is a Great Pyrenees/Maremma who has spent her life as a working livestock guardian dog, first in Kansas and later in Texas. Bobby was raised with goats, and had some exposure to chickens, but always seemed more interested in playing with the other dogs than in protecting the livestock. We moved him into the house for some basic training, such as how to walk on a leash, as well as crate-training and house/potty-training. He also got a refresher course in good manners around chickens. He did really well with all of these changes, but didn't really seem HAPPY in the house, so we moved him into one of our paddocks. Bobby seems happier living outside, but will come in the house if that's what you ask. He has good guardian instincts as far as walking the perimeter and barking when he hears coyotes. We think the best home for Bobby might be as a family guardian on a small homestead, where he can live outside, but be allowed to come inside during thunderstorms, which frighten him. He is very shy on meeting new people, so he needs an adopter with the patience to earn his trust. He also needs secure fencing that is at least 5' tall. He hasn't challenged the fencing at Windsong Ranch, but because of his skittishness with strangers, we don't feel safe putting him in a new home with fencing shorter than 4'. Once a fearful dog goes over the fence, it can be almost impossible to get them home again.

If Bobby looks like just the companion you need in your life, please submit your application at www.bluebonnetrescue.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Albus is a handsome Great Pyrenees male who was picked up as a stray by some nice people who took him into their home. Albus is a great dog -- he is good with other dogs, cats, and children. At a recent adoption event, he was friendly with everyone and would let anyone come up and pet and love on him. He is good on a leash, sits on command, and doesn't bark as much as some Pyrenees. Albus is fully housetrained, is gentle, calm, and easygoing.

BUT, Albus has one major issue that MUST be considered by any potential adopter. He has major separation anxiety, and also has anxiety during storms (regardless of whether WE hear thunder, rainstorms upset Albus). Fireworks and gunfire terrify him. Albus must be in a home where one of his humans is home most of the time and where he has at least one other Great Pyrenees (preferably one as large as he is) to keep him company. His new home MUST have a secure 6' (or taller) fence, preferably wrought iron or chain link so he has a view of the world around him. As we said, Albus is a truly wonderful dog, and in the right setting (like his current foster home at Windsong Ranch), Albus is a very easy dog to manage.

If you have another big Pyr and are retired or work from home, and if you have a nice big yard with great fencing, please consider Albus as your new companion. He is worth the extra attention he needs during times of stress.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Gabriel is a stunningly handsome male with one blue eye and one brown eye. He came from an extreme hoarding case in Arizona where the adult dogs had been left in the field and not socialized with people. Gabriel was the alpha male of the group. All of these dogs were fearful of people in the beginning, and Gabriel was so aggressive that he had to be tranquilized just to be brought in to the shelter. He's still not comfortable on a leash, but at least he DOES walk now rather than fight it. He wags his tail and does the puppy play-bow, so we know he WANTS to trust us. It's just that people haven't given him much reason to trust in the past.

Gabriel is a fierce livestock guardian, and is especially protective of babies of any kind, whether it's a tiny Nigerian Dwarf goat kid or a longhorn bull calf. He can be aggressive with people that he doesn't know, so his adopter will need to be a strong leader, committed to taking the time necessary to earn his trust and help him grow into a more socialized dog.

During his time with us, Gabriel has shown a real aversion to being inside the house, so please don't think that this is a dog you will adopt and turn into a couch potato. He's also a dog who requires special handling for trips to the vet. He will get in our van willingly and rides well. But once we get to the vet's office, we typically muzzle him for everyone's safety. If we need to do anything invasive -- even something as simple as a thorough ear-cleaning, we usually sedate him so the vet and vet techs can work without worry that he will react negatively.

Gabriel is available ONLY to a working home with an adopter who has experience with unsocialized dogs. He also requires secure fencing that is AT LEAST 5' tall. He can go over 5' tall fencing, so if you live on smaller acreage, you either need fencing taller than 5', invisible fence inside the physical fence, or you need to live in an area that is sparsely populated, because it would not be safe for him to go over your fence and engage with neighbors.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Petra is one of seven dogs who came into rescue together as working LGDs. They spent their lives guarding goats on a 9600 acre ranch in the Texas Panhandle and were never properly socialized before coming to Bluebonnet. Petra was adopted then returned to us when she started climbing over the 4' fences at her new home. She returned to our pastures, which are enclosed with 5' fences, and everything was good, until she started going over OUR fences too.

We moved Petra to the house, where we have a yard with 6' tall fencing. She has assimilated into the routine of living inside the house, and even chooses to sleep in the crate most days, not because we put her there, but just because we keep the doors open on all our crates so the dogs learn to accept them as just another part of the furniture.

Petra is still very shy on meeting new people, but she does enjoy petting from her family. She is not one to bark unnecessarily, so she could be a great companion for someone who lives in town and has neighbors to consider.

Petra gets along with other dogs unless they bother her during meal times. Then, she doesn't hesitate to defend her bowl. She has never been one to play with other dogs, but recently, she has started making overtures to the male dogs in her foster home, trying to get them to play with her. Given her shy nature, we think it would be wonderful for Petra to have a confident dog in the home, so she can continue to follow that example, as she does in her foster home. She walks well on a leash, and is accustomed to walking with one or more big dogs.

If you think Petra would be the perfect addition to your family, please visit our website to read about our adoption process and submit your application.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.UPDATE:

In the summer of 2019, Crockett sustained a broken leg; surgery to repair it was not successful, so the leg was amputated. He gets around well in spite of becoming a tripod late in life, but the older he gets, the more difficult it is for him to get up. Once he's up, he moves much more quickly than you might expect for a senior dog!

After a lifetime of living in the pasture as a livestock guardian, Crockett is now semi-retired. He has a cushy bed in the barn, and he is allowed to go between the pasture and our front entry area (fenced, of course). After his surgery and during his recuperation, Crockett lived in the house, and he behaved very nicely. But he was not happy living inside, and was jubilant when we took him back out to the pasture. After every meal, we let him decide whether he wants to go back to the pasture or stay in the barn. If he stays in the barn, he has an open door to our front entry area, which he likes because it's more level and thus easier for him to maneuver. From this area, we can see that he feels like he's guarding us against intruders, since this is where our front gate and driveway are. Even though it's clear he relishes THAT job, his LGD roots also pull him back to the pasture frequently, so he spends about half his time there, as part of a team of LGDs protecting our Nigerian Dwarf bucks.

If you are interested in giving Crockett a safe place to retire and feel like he is still doing an important job, please visit our website to read about our adoption process and submit your application.

ORIGINAL BIO:

Crockett has been a hard-working man for pretty much his whole life. He has guarded goats, cattle, donkeys, and horses in the past, and now lives in a pasture with our Nigerian Dwarf goats.

Crockett
has proven safe with our livestock and is a fierce guardian. He can be aggressive with people that he doesn't know, so his adopter will need to be a strong leader and committed to taking the time necessary to earn his trust.

NOTE: Crockett is sporting a "Summer Cut" in some of these photos because his coat was so matted when he came to use that the best remedy was to shave and start over. He now has a full, long plush coat. We do not recommend shaving double-coated dogs like Great Pyrenees, but in Crockett's case it became necessary.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.UPDATE: In September 2020, Casper's left eye was swollen and inflamed, so we made an emergency trip to the vet. We treated him for uveitis, which helped, but he still had more pressure in that eye than is safe/healthy. With a diagnosis of glaucoma and no likelihood that further treatment would make a difference, his eye was removed. He doesn't seem to mind having just one eye, and in terms of long-term care, the vet just advised that we need to keep close watch on his other eye for signs that he may be developing glaucoma again.

*******************************************

ORIGINAL BIO:

One thing we should say right upfront -- we really are just guessing about Casper's breeds. He is very strong, and pulls on the leash in a way that reminds us of a sled dog. He looks a lot like another dog we rescued last year, whose parents were known to be a Great Pyrenees and a Siberian Husky. But he also has just the tiniest bit of red/gold on the edges of his semi-prick ears, and that reminds us of other dogs we have rescued, including a white Shiba Inu, a Pyr/Aussie mix, and a Pyr/Red Heeler mix. His tail is an interesting anomaly too. It's about half the length of a normal tail; he doesn't seem to be sensitive when we touch his tail, so we think it's possible that his tail has always been like this, or if it was cut short due to an accident or injury, it was long ago and left no residual sensitivity. It almost makes us think that maybe he has a naturally bobtailed breed in his family tree -- some Aussies and Heelers are naturally bobtailed and others have docked tails. If you are as curious as we are, maybe your budget would allow you to donate a DNA test so we could find out what contributors there are to Casper's unique good looks.

Casper is very friendly with his foster family, and he is very affectionate, leaning into us frequently to encourage us to pet him. He has done OK meeting people at adoption events, but he is not usually friendly with visitors to his foster home. He is very protective of his home and family, and must be crated or put in a different room when visitors come.

He should NOT go to a home with cats, as he will chase them every chance he gets, and seems to mean harm to them, not a fun game of chase.

Casper gets along OK with other dogs, but sometimes gets nervous when a dog who is larger than he is invades his space. He lives in peace with many dogs in his foster home, but would do best in a home where he is the only dog or at least the largest dog.

Casper enjoys spending time in the yard, but he also has good manners in the house -- no potty accidents, no chewing or other destructive behavior.

He definitely needs a human family who is strong and can manage him on the leash, because HE is strong and can get excited and pull on the leash very hard.

If Casper sounds like just the dog you have been looking for, please submit an application on our website and we'll be glad to schedule a Meet & Greet where you can see for yourself what a sweet, handsome boy he really is.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING STERLING, PLEASE GO TO THE MAKE A DIFFERENCE RESCUE FACEBOOK PAGE AND SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE THAT INCLUDES YOUR PHONE NUMBER AND EMAIL ADDRESS.

Sterling is a gorgeous 3 year old Pointer mix. Sterling loves being around people!! She loves to play, hang out with people, give kisses and cuddle. She is good with other dogs and needs to have another dog to play with in her forever home. We do not know how she is with cats. She has lots of energy and needs to be exercised regularly. Sterling needs to work on consistently executing her basic commands. Sterling has been working on her leash manners and is very strong. She would do best with children 5 years old or older. Sterling's forever home is required to have a fenced yard where she can safely run and play. Sterling is spayed, up to date on her vaccinations and on heartworm preventive as well as house and crate trained. This fantastic girl cannot wait to meet his forever family who will love and spoil her for the rest of her life!!!!


All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or outside the U.S. adoptions or fosters. Sterling's adoption fee is $275.

animal.description:
Reecy is a goofy and sweet 7 year old mix! We're not 100% sure of her mix but her body looks Great Pyrenees and her face looks more like a Bull dog--what an interesting mix! Reecy is a big girl, who isn't fully aware of her size. She weighs about 75 lbs and although she is quite strong, volunteers love taking her for a walk. She greets everyone with exuberance--be ready for a kiss! She loves her toys and will play quietly by herself while you're in your Zoom meeting. She may make a cameo appearance from time to time just to say hi to everyone. She will keep you smiling. Reecy is looking for her forever family--ideally one that will play with her every day and continue her training.

Here at NMAR, we don't just find good homes for our dogs, we find the the specific good home for each specific dog. While we work towards those matches, our dogs are safe and happy in foster homes, or in our home-like shelter, where they have the chance to learn some life skills and show us what they need to be happy and healthy.

REQUIREMENTS:  Reecy is dog selective but LOVES people!  She is looking for a home where she is the only pet. Due to her size and personality, she also needs a home with a fenced yard. 

Adoption fee is $125 and includes: spay/neuter, parvo/distemper series of shots, rabies (if dog is old enough), bordatella, heartworm preventative while here, worming, and microchip.

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting one of our dogs, please visit our website and fill out an application: NorthMeckAnimalRescue.org

animal.description:
**MEDICAL HOLD**

Sadie is a NWFLGDR alumni - a beautiful 7 year old TALL velvet black dane girl who loves her humans. Sadie was surrendered back to the rescue through no fault of her own - a product of divorce.

She is great with other dogs, kids, cats - a social girl and a bit of a boss - but a low key, easy going, well behaved boss. She is currently living in a foster home with three cats, and a lazy older female dane named Penny. Penny and Sadie coexist nicely together their days consist of deciding to sleep on the bed, sleep on the couch, sleep on the futon, sleep on the dog beds, beg for snacks, and/or peruse the kitchen for snacks to kidnap....decisions decisions decisions. 

She has previously lived in a home with a young and older children, dogs, and cats - Sadie was great with them all!

Sadie is crate trained, potty trained, does pretty well on a leash, is used to a gentle leader. Sadie isn't a big fan of thunderstorms, and gets anxious when it's thundering a lot. Like a typical dane... trying to get her outside to do her business when it's raining hard will be a challenge... she HATES going outside in the rain and would rather hold it for 24 hours.

All in all though, Sadie is a lovebug and deserves a forever family. She's got so much love to give.

Could you be the one?

Sadie is currently being treated for a severe UTI and slight urinary incontinence that may be caused by the UTI. 

Sadie's adoption fee is $300. To apply to adopt Sadie go to www.nwflgdr.com/adoption.html.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR DOES NOT TRANSPORT. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Maya is a high-spirited hound/ terrier mix with a lot of personality! She loves to play and loves to be loved on. She would adore a family who loves the outdoors and wants to take their loyal companion with them.Due to Mayas energy level, an adult only home or a home with older children is preferred. Maya would flourish in a home with a yard where she can run and play and enjoy the outdoors. She soaks up all that attention and is always happy.

animal.description: Luna is a beautiful, sweet young girl, probably born in late 2016, and currently weighs 48 pounds (though she was a starved 36 pounds when she first arrived).  Guessing she is a Lab and possibly Pitbull Terrier mix. When she knows and trusts her environment, Luna is loving and happy and playful - especially with other dogs - she is the sweetest playmate.  But she is also a talented escape artist: she can climb fences of any height and can escape from crates that are not robustly reinforced.  She does not seem to be destructive, mostly rides really nicely in a car, walks pretty well on a leash (though will occasionally lunge after cars), and is house and crate trained if she gets out regularly to do her business. Luna is currently on TRAZADONE for anti-anxiety. She is doing pretty well and is so lovable and adorable once she knows and trusts you. Luna has STRANGER DANGER when she meets new people.  Her best home is with an EXPERIENCED FEMALE adopter who is home as much as possible, and ideally, but not necessarily) another playful friendly dog, and does not have a lot of visitors to the home.  NO CATS.  NO CHILDREN.  If you are interested in meeting Luna please contact Bev at 804-248-3042 or trampsrescue@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Darla is an 11 year old, female, spayed, Boxer/Cattle Dog mix. Darla is very eager to please her human. She loves the beach and swimming, going for walks and car rides. She knows her commands well (sit, stay, shake and lay down). She will lay her head all the way onto the floor when you tell her "all the way down". She is a very quick learner. She loves to play fetch and playing with squeaky toys. She also loves getting packages in the mail...she will wait patiently for you to open the package and then beg for any bubble wrap. She will pop each bubble and then bring the plastic back to you.She is kennel trained and will even go to her kennel when she thinks that you are about to leave. Darla is picky about which dogs she likes and doesn't like. She would do best as an only dog. If you have any questions, please contact us at hhfrescue@gmail.com. If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application at www.hhfrescue.org. Thank you for considering a rescued dog.The adoption fee includes vaccinations, bordetella, deworming, rabies, spay/neuter, microchip, a lifetime registration of the microchip, and sales tax. If adopting a puppy, the rabies and spay/neuter will be done at the same time by our vet once they are 4 months old and billed to us. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

animal.description:
Sophie is a show-stopping, beautiful girl with pure white, gorgeous fur and an adorable face. She is very affectionate. She is also very energetic and loves to play. She is crate-trained and doesn't complain about spending time there. Sophie will sit (after due consideration) for the right treats and give you the Pyr paw (shake) since it's the polite thing to do. Sophie loves her walks and play time with squeaky toys. Having a young playful male dog would be ideal for her and would help her burn off excess energy. Sophie has had a tough start, so her adopter will have to be willing to continue her training. She can be very stubborn, she engages in resource guarding (food especially) and she will jump up to play without being invited, including on walks (this last behavior can be resolved with a firm "No!" however). She also has some degree of separation anxiety but willingly goes into her crate. Sophie will be an immensely rewarding pet for the right person or people—experienced Pyr owners who are willing to work with her. There should be no children or cats in Sophie's new home, but a young male Pyr or similarly sized dog would be ideal. Please help Sophie be the best dog she can be!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

DFW AREA ADOPTERS ONLY

Meet Tucker! Or as we affectionately call him “ Tuck Tuck”
Tucker needs a home with another dog to play with.
Tucker is three  years old whose gentle and sweet nature will melt your heart! 
First you must gain his trust as he sadly is learning not all humans are bad and he missed out on that critical social interaction as a puppy. Patience, love, stability and a quiet environment along with other dogs will help build his confidence in a new environment. 
A few of his favorite things are big comfy beds, chew toys, treats, playtime with his foster pack and absolutely loves the outdoors, chasing bunnies out of the yard and snuggle time at the end of the day seems to be his all time fave! 
He is currently learning how to be a hound, walk on a leash and ride in the car. He is still very fearful of new things, people and places but continues to make progress slowly. 
Tucker was dealt a bad hand early in life and we are hoping to find that perfect match to give him the life he so deserves!

** Special Needs - Emotional **

Hey, Lily Squirt here!! I'm back with my foster family. I'm a little sad because I love my adoptive family and miss them. If you are looking for a sweet, loving and active girl I'm the dog for you!! But my new forever home should be just me as an only dog. Can't wait to meet you!

animal.description: Cordel arrived at Friends for Life, Inc, on April 11, 2018, needing a new home.  He's been neutered, had been housebroken in his previous home, slept in a crate at night, was taught to Sit on command (especially for food!), and sometimes comes when called (in a fenced area).  He's full of energy and will need plenty of exercise. He doesn't seem to be too interested in fetching, although he'll chase a ball, etc. a couple of times.  He learned how the doggie door operates in two seconds.  He's SHARP and he'll be one step ahead of you if you don't pay attention.  He has "looks" that he gives that are hilarious.  He was evaluated by a trainer in April 2018 and was declared not to have "a mean bone in his body".  He shares his yard area at this time with 3 neutered males: Parker, a brindle hound/Lab mix about Cordel's size, and Rascal, a feisty 18 lb little guy; and Oscar, a 13 lb fella who's blind. Cordel's history as I know it is that he somehow got a broken leg when he was about 3-4 months old and was going to be destroyed.  A young woman offered to take him, and she and her husband took him to the vet and had the leg set, had him vaccinated, housebroke him, and taught him to Sit.  You can't tell at all that one of his legs was broken.  He needs a home where he will once again be a loved member of the family.  Plan to make sure that he has exercise daily or twice daily, and mental stimulation.  THIS IS A GREAT DOG!  He'll return your efforts ten-fold and be an attentive, sweet-tempered companion that will keep you chuckling for the next 10-12 years! Please go to FFL's facebook page for videos of Cordel. Our page is Friends for Life, Inc in LEWISBURG, WV. (There are lots of Friends for Life organizations!) NOTE: He will only be adopted as a companion, not as a hunting dog.

animal.description:
Fish is roughly 3 years old, breed undetermined. He originally came to us with Demadex mange, but has since been cleared up! He is neutered and current on vaccines. Fish is your typical GOTTA GET INTO EVERYTHING AND TOUCH EVERYTHING puppy, and therefore blankets are a no go lol. He thinks it's fun to shred them. Fish is very intelligent and has learned, sit, and stay very quickly! That intelligence if not properly worked with will get him into trouble. He loves to work, and go and do! Does great on a leash!

 Fish needs to be the only pet in his home.

While no dog is perfect, as a rescue we try to make our adopters fully aware of any and all behavior issues/concerns so as to set everyone up for success. *Fish is currently working on some minor behavior issues when it comes to his food, he gets very excited and will get upset if someone else is eating when he's not. He has made major progress. While Fish would make a fantastic family member, we do not recommend his puppy antics for beginner pet parents.

*Jaded Paws Rescue is a 501c3 foster run organization, and we do not have a kennel facility for the general public to come and visit. We do this because we find our animals will be much more accustomed to the home environment when the time comes that they get adopted! If you'd like to meet a Jaded Paws Pet, simply email us and we can schedule a meet and greet that is compatible with your schedule. Our adoption process includes an adoption application, a meet and greet and a 7-day adoption trial at the prospective family's home before the adoption is official. Our adoption fees are as follows: Puppies/Adults: $125 Senior dogs: $75 Cats:$50*

animal.description:
I am a very sweet, 15 yr old, 13 lb white Bichon Poodle Mix. My birthday is May 18, 2005. My owner became very ill and was unable to continue to care for me. 

I am an active very playful little girl. I love to be loved and really enjoy belly rubs. I get along great with the other pupsters and enjoy romping and playing with them. Just give me a toy and I think I am in heaven. I did have mammary tumors and test results indicate a Grade 2. I would love a home with another pupster to play with and a fenced in yard to enjoy. I prefer no small children.

My diet is an extremely important factor in my overall health. Mom wanted to feed us the very best diet available, so Peke A Tzu Rescue became a distributor for Oma's Pride Raw Food products. I am enjoying a yummy turkey & veggie mix raw diet now. Mom alternates between turkey, beef and chicken raw diets. Please read about my special diet. Mom adds the following supplements: digestive enzymes, probiotics, kelp, DMG and salmon oil for a healthy balanced meal. I hope that my forever Mom/Dad will love me enough to keep me on a raw diet.

I am spayed, current on vaccinations, tested heart worm negative, on a monthly heartworm prevention and natural flea protection. I am house trained and do well during grooming.

My adoption fee is $300.

If you would like to see what our pupsters are up to on a daily basis please visit our Foster Journal at www.pekeatzurescue.com. Also our online application is available on our website.

animal.description:
Meet Lady! Lady is a 6 year old Lab/Shepherd mix. Lady needs a very competent and experienced owner, one that has had experience in handling GSD/Malinois/Belgain Shepherds before. She would make a great Police Dog as she has a strong desire to be a pack leader and a high prey drive, and would do well with training and having a 'job.' Lady needs to be an only animal home and is not recommended for a home with children!
If you are interested in making Lady a part of your family, fill out an application at www.barktownrescur.org

LADY'S ADOPTION FEE IS $160 The shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at the dog's predominant breed or breed mix. We strongly encourage you to select your new pet by looking at each dog's individual personality and pet qualities rather than relying on a breed label that is only our best guess.

Our adoption fees vary from $150 and up. All of our dogs are up to date on vaccines, heart worm preventives, and flea/tick medication, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Portions of your adoption fee also help care for the sick and injured animals that we take in. Thank you for supporting us and considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Wally is a friendly guy that loves to play. He comes complete with his own little buddy, Biscuit. Biscuit is a semi-feral female dog that decided she loves Wally and will only go where he goes. This wasn't exactly what we planned, but love has no boundaries.

Wally is a great little dog that will make a good family pet, but no small children. He does not like to be medicated. If you try to put a pill in his mouth you will probably lose a finger or two. He will gladly take his meds in cheese or dog food. Shots are also a live changing experience. Your vet will LOVE Wally, till he goes to stick him.

Wally and Biscuit can be adopted locally in Texas or we can work with one of the transporters to deliver them to Washington, Portland, Minnesota, Vermont or all along the East Coast. Their adoption fee is $250 and transport is $320. To adopt this pair please visit our website www.adoggie4you.org and fill out an application. Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an application on file to ensure the dog is a match

animal.description:
IF YOU CAN OPEN YOUR HEART AND HOME TO FOSTER KINSALE, PLEASE GO TO THE MAKE A DIFFERENCE RESCUE FACEBOOK PAGE AND SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE THAT INCLUDES YOUR PHONE NUMBER AND EMAIL ADDRESS.

Hi! My name is Kinsale, named after the port town in Ireland. Most people call me Kinsey though. I am an adorable 5 year old shepherd mix who is looking for my forever home. I have lots of energy, but after a good walk or run I love to come inside and chill. I would be in heaven if I could curl up on the couch with you in the evening and sleep snuggled next to you in bed. I am spayed, house broken, and crate trained.My vaccinations are up to date and I am on monthly heart worm preventative.  I am super smart, learning new tricks and commands quickly. I need a family with a nice yard and a PRIVACY fence, so I have space to run and play safely. NO TIE OUTS OR INVISIBLE FENCES.  I’m fast and agile, and I can climb chain link fences when I see a squirrel or rabbit I might want to chase. I have lived with other dogs in the past, but I need to be carefully introduced to new dog friends to make sure we get along. NO CATS!!! I would do best with children 10 years old and older. I cannot wait to meet my forever family who will love and cherish me for the rest of my life.

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or outside the U.S. adoptions or fosters. Kinsale's adoption fee is $275.

animal.description:
Hank is a basset hound mix. Don't let the picture fool you he is about 71 pounds. He is a wonderful boy who like most hounds is led by his nose. He definitely is a lover and enjoys being with people. We would love to see him in a home where he has lots of interaction with people of all ages. He has been good with other dogs  but seems to want to chase the kitties. He is also not good with young children. Definitely would love regular amount of exercise and probably would not be good in an apartment setting because of his expressive voice.

He is a male, neutered, microchipped, and current on all his vaccines. His adoption fee is $350 and helps Ensure that Valhalla rescue can continue to help dogs in need like Hank.


We are 501 c 3, all volunteer organization and we greatly appreciate you choosing to adopt and not shop and for looking at one of our dogs. Good luck on your search and if you  have any questions 360-559-4972, please feel free to contact us at Valhallarescue@gmail.com or by calling us at  and one of our volunteers will get back to you as soon as possible to answer any questions you might have.
If you would like to submit an application please visit our website at Valhallarescue.org where you will find it online application on our adoption page. 

Thank you so much for looking at a rescue dog.

animal.description: Hi! I'm Nala...sweet, silly, and somewhat shy. I'm looking for someone who will give me a bit of time to get to know me! A girl just can't throw herself at the first human who comes along, after all. Once I get to know you and you show me you are a good person, and maybe give me some treats (like hotdogs) I melt like butter. And I smile! (like in my picture) I do like getting out for walks, and doing a little running around, but I don't need a super high energy family. I can be quite the couch potato! But since I can be sensitive I would do best in a quiet home without a lot of chaos. So I'd probably be good with older teens who understand I like a slower pace and steady routine. I'd prefer being the only pet princess in the house, too. I am housetrained, and crate trained, and I weigh about 60 pounds. Are you the one who can let me have time to adjust to new situations, and then enjoy lots of love and loyalty after that? Let's find out!

animal.description:
IF THIS LISTING IS STILL UP, they are still available for adoption!   Inquiries asking about availability will not be answered. E-mails or contact forms that are submitted prior to completing an adoption application will not be answered.

***Please read this first, as it answers the majority of questions we receive***

Please do not contact us about specific dogs until you have completed our Adoption Application FIRST --- located at www.aussierescue.org

Once we receive your application, we will contact you. This chapter only receives applications from applicants living in Texas and Oklahoma. If you live outside of TX or OK, you will need to contact our organizations Management Team first: managementteam2@yahoo.com). Out-of-state adoptions are considered on a case-by-case basis.

Our organization requires prospective adopters to complete an approval process prior to meeting with dogs in our program. This includes:

*Completion of Adoption Application
*Veterinarian Check
*Reference Checks (non-relatives)
*Home Visit

Our ultimate goal is to screen and counsel potential homes to the best of our ability in an effort to find the most perfect match and fit for their lifestyle.

Please keep in mind that color and appearance of the available dog is last on our priority list, and will have no bearing on adoption placement decisions.

Please refrain from contacting members of our organization or asking about specific dogs/potential matches until after your screening process has been completed and approved. 

***Our organization requires a donation of $300 to adopt.***
--------------------------------------------------------

ABOUT GALA:
Rep: Kim Griswold / kimgriswold@att.net

Gala is located in Bedford, TX and it is required that you travel there to meet her in person to adopt, no exceptions. We do need the entire party to be involved when meeting available dogs, including every family member and dog(s) that currently live in your home. 

Gala came to us with 24 other aussies, including her mother and brother, when a producer went out of business.  

Gala is a beautiful 2-year-old black tri female who has been in foster care far too long.  She is a great size at just 38 lbs.  She is crate trained, housebroken, and is very loving with her “family”.  She is smart, learns quickly, is biddable, is energetic but does have an off switch.  
 
In September 2019 she had a freak accident and broke two vertebrae in her back.  She had surgery to repair the break.  Being the determined and optimistic girl that she is, she has recovered nicely and her happy personality has not been affected. We continue to do physical therapy to strengthen her back legs but they may always be less than perfect and she probably will never move with the grace and beauty that she did before the injury.  However, that does not keep her from being a normal dog.  She can still run like the wind, play fetch, swim, hike, and do things like nose work that do not require any jumping.  
 
Gala has been through a lot of training.  Probably far more than most foster dogs would get as she needed a mental outlet for her energy.  She has been through puppy training, manners classes, agility, dock jumping, and nose work.  While she can no longer do things that require jumping, she is able to participate in traditional obedience, rally, and nose work.
 
Her favorite things are playing fetch, running, and swimming.  Running while squeaking a toy at the same time is the best!   When she is playing with a toy, she trots around with it in her mouth, squeaking it to beat the band and proud as punch.  She is also very food motivated and will do almost anything for food!  
 
Gala wasn’t extremely interested in human touch when she was very young (she came to ARPH at just 5 weeks old) but as she has matured, she has figured out that belly rubs and massages are good things.  She really is a happy girl and her nubbin and grin show that.  She does give kisses (too many sometimes) and has even learned to snuggle.  
 
Even though Gala has been exposed to a multitude of different people, places, and experiences, she is still unsure about new people and dogs she hasn't seen before.  She is especially sensitive to people and dogs staring at her as well as some movement (people moving from sitting to standing, dogs running).  She does bark at other dogs when she sees them but is friendly with dogs once she meets them.  She does take some time to warm up to people (Treats help immensely!), but we know that she is very capable of bonding with people in a new home as she has made “vacation” visits to other foster homes and when given time to adjust to the new environment, she did well.  She has shown no aggression with any people or dogs. And she loves playing bitey face and wrestling with the dogs in the foster home.
 
Gala’s perfect home would be an active home along the lines of walking, hiking, swimming, or ongoing training.  The injury has slowed her down only a little; she still has plenty of spunk and energy.  Being injured did not turn her into a couch potato. So, while she may not have the physical abilities she did before, she will still need plenty of physical and mental exercise. It will be important to keep her weight down. They will also need to be prepared to deal with any issues with the hardware in her back and the possibility of arthritis in the future.  A home with another dog that is easy going (but not a push over) might be helpful with continuing to improve her confidence.  She has done well in homes with multiple dogs (even small dogs). A home without children is best but a home with older children (12 and above) who behave appropriately around dogs might be okay.  Adopters will need to be patient and understanding and continue working with her reserve with people, strange dogs & situations, and the barking that sometimes goes along with those.   She will initially bond with a favorite person in the home but will eventually adjust to (and seek out) all occupants. 
 
Gala deserves to be in her forever home.  She has improved so much in the time she has been with ARPH.  Someone just needs to be willing to give her a chance, even though she doesn't necessarily make a great first impression.

Rex was adopted from SQ Rescue as a puppy but returned after his family moved. They no longer had a suitable situation for Rex and he is looking for a new family. He is approximately two years old, neutered, micro-chipped and current on vaccinations. Rex is high energy dog that would do well with an active family. A FENCED YARD IS A MUST. Rex gets along well with other dogs but is still a little shy to initiate play. Rex has completed a three-week doggie Boot Camp and is very sweet boy but needs a dog savvy owner because he can become anxious and does better with an alpha owner who will give him boundaries and structure. We do not think a home with children (might be ok with teenagers at least 15/16 if experienced with dogs) would be suitable as he can be overly energetic .

Adoption fee: (Cash/Check) $175 (Credit/Debit) $180. This includes vet care and vaccines up until adoption, spaying/neutering, and microchip. If you are interested in this wonderful pet, please complete an online application at sqrescueinc.org.  Incomplete/missing information will delay processing. Noah's Arks Rescue is all about giving an Abused Animal a second chance at life and to experience what true love is. We then provide rehab physically and mentally to prepare them for their new home and new life. We are located in Ridgeland, SC., and are by appointment only. All of our dogs are at our Rehabilitation Center either in hospice care or being loved on by staff until we find them forever homes. animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.BJ was originally named Bon Jour, but her name was shortened by her previous owners. She got the name by being a vocal little lady who said a loud 'Hello' to everyone she met. Unfortunately, when BJ's owners had to go into a retirement / assisted living facility, Baby still wanted to talk to everyone walking by. She had never been in a multi-unit dwelling environment, and her constant barking at all the new and strange sounds, scents, and movement made it impossible for her to stay there.
BJ is a good girl, she's just vocal. She's very sweet once she knows you're her friend, and she is a good leash walker who is comfy around adults. BJ can be snarky around other dogs sometimes- it's not that she doesn't like them, it's more as though she sees no purpose for them. Diva that she is, BJ prefers to get all the attention.
At 7 - 10 years old, BJ looks and acts half that age, and she is generally in very good health. The only exception is that her previous owners sent her with Proin, a medication she takes every evening. They said it keeps her from having urinary accidents or needing to go during the night. We haven't had her long enough to know whether it's truly necessary or not, but we have notice no problems with her house training, so there's probably no need to change anything as long as it's working.
This cute lady deserves a loving forever home. She's loyal, has personality, and the perfect dog for the right situation. BJ is ready to say 'Hello' to a great furever home!

animal.description:
UPDATED 1/5/2021

Biscuit's Foster Mom had a DNA test done on him,  This guy is no Coonhound!  He is a Boxer (25%) mixed with several other breeds.  He is quite an interesting mix!  He is still looking for that perfect match.  Will it be with you?

UPDATED 8/25/2020.  

Biscuit is a 70 lb, handsome boy, who is in search of a home free of worry and excitement. He loves the company of other dogs. Biscuit has learned that if you have a dog, he knows you are a good person. He has had a rough past, wherein people and tension stress him out to the point of becoming reactive. A home with one or two adults, who do not have a lot of foot traffic in and out of their home and who like to walk or hike would be ideal. 
 
Biscuit's favorite things to do are go for car rides and take long walks in the park or hikes in the woods. He does well for grooming and rather enjoys a bath and a brush. He likes to chew on bones, is crate trained and housebroken. Once Biscuit is bonded with you, he loves you forever. He will tolerate being around people but isn’t one to go to dog parks or places where others are going to want to pet him or engage him directly. 

Biscuit is currently living with a trainer, who would love to see him adopted by someone who will commit to helping him continue to expand his social circle, someone who will be willing to continue his training and work to establish trust through a slow transition. We realize Biscuit is not perfect, but for the right person he can be the perfect match!

Adoption application, home visit and adoption fee required. If you would like to apply for adoption, please complete the online application at www.furryfriendsnetwork.com. Look under ADOPT tab. Please also read Our Expectations prior to applying. Contact generalinfo@furryfriendsnetwork.com for questions or if issues are encountered with the adoption application or general adoption process.

Foster Homes are desperately needed in order to help more animals like this one. Please consider opening your heart and home to a homeless animal. To find out more about becoming a Foster Parent, see our website at www.furryfriendsnetwork.com. Look under VOLUNTEER tab.

Pet ID: Amy P

animal.description: Willow was born in August of 2006 and weighs about 40 pounds. She is a special girl who has made a miraculous emotional recovery after suffering severe abuse. She was terrified when she first came to us after being dragged down the road when she couldn't run along the car any longer. She was emotionally flat for weeks and wouldn't respond to anyone until another dog came and earned her trust. Soon she discovered she could also trust people as well. Now she is an affectionate lady who is easy to bathe, walks well on a leash and loves to get affection. She likes to curl up on her dog bed and is content just hanging out in the house staying close to her people. When she is outside she likes to play with rocks or buckets and will entertain herself for hours with them. If you have a big heart and are willing to provide this sweet lady with the love and care she deserves please give her a chance. Willow deserves to have some pleasure in her golden years given that she had so little during her early life.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Schatzi came into rescue when her beloved owner was battling a serious illness and soon passed away. When she still had Schatzi, she found it easiest to just leave food out for her. She was well loved, but not being able to keep her under the circumstances, Schatzi was listed on a Facebook for-sale/free group site and ATDR brought her into their fold severely overweight. Thanks to her foster mom putting her on the Biggest Loser diet plan, she is now down to 14 pounds! Being a miniature dachshund who should usually weigh in the 10-pound range, she still has a ways to go, but for now 'Good job Schatzi! Keep up the good work and you'll get there.' Schatzi has allergies and some hair loss. Her foster mom now has her on allergy shots which seem to be helping. We're not sure if this will be seasonal or if she will need the shots year-round. ATDR and Schatzi are taking it one step at a time and thankful for every small victory. Even with all the things going on in Schatzi's precious little life, she is a very sweet and loving baby. She is completely housetrained and crate trained, although she doesn't require crating when her foster mom is away from home. Other than the few health issues listed here, she's the perfect dog! Schatzi is so deserving of a loving forever home, but she wouldn't be a good apartment dog. She 'talks' to her foster family by barking and gets very excited when they arrive home, barking many sweet hellos! If you have it in your heart to offer Schatzi a devoted forever home where she will be loved and properly cared for, please fill out an adoption application for her. She's oh so worthy of the best home out there!3.21.20 Upate: Just look at this girl now! She's done an AMAZING job on her diet! We're so happy to see her much thinner and healthier! Good job Schatzi!!!
animal.name: Schatzi

animal.description:

He loves his cozy dog bed, soft blankets, treats, riding in the car, going for walks, attention and butt scratches from his people, and toys. He loves playing fetch and tug. It's so cute when he gets giddy, gallops around, and is super happy- he has the best smile. He makes really adorable sounds when you get home, he wants to do something, or he's just really excited- sometimes like Chewbacca. Rocky would do best as an only dog. This guy really likes to take baths- he can be found sitting pretty in the bathroom or even standing in the bathtub looking at the faucet wondering why the water is not coming out when he wants it to. He would do better in a home without kids or one with older kids that understand his boundaries. He is wonderfully housebroken and crate trained. Rocky has been through professional training, so is great on a leash, knows heel, auto-sit, sit, down, stay, and head and hand motions. His adoption will include sessions with his trainer. Most importantly, he needs a patient person or family that gives him space to get used to his new people. It is well worth the wait though because he makes the best companion once he trusts you and knows you respect his boundaries. He can be nervous around strangers and doesn't like to be touched/reached for by strangers straight away upon meeting them. He is such a loving creature to his people, extremely handsome, and provides endless laughter, smiles and entertainment!

animal.description:
Melody Skye is a sweet hound mix who has been looking for her forever home for a couple years with SAAP. Melody Skye loves to chase a frisbee and is a champ at playing keep away! She loves to go on walks and be with her people. She is crate trained and house trained like a good doggie. A fenced in yard would be great for Skye, but she can climb over some fences and should not be left in the yard alone.

Melody Skye is looking for a special adopter who will help continue her training. This precious girl was frightened when fireworks were lit in the neighborhood and as a result became reactive to other dogs. Because of this, Skye needs to be the only pet. Skye has been professionally trained by Tori Roser at Pawlished Dog Training. Her future home would get a free follow up visit with Tori to learn the skills she has been taught. Tori is also there in case her new home has questions as Melody adjusts to her new life.

Overall, Melody Skye would be perfect for a home looking to add a companion who is ready to start having adventures!

animal.description:
POINTER MIX; Sleek cream jacket with light brown dappling; brown ears and mask around face. 61lbs
FEMALE ADULT; Est DOB:  March 2015
ARRIVAL: October 4, 2017
HISTORY:  Olive was brought in as a stray with her mom and sister. She was adopted within a month, but was returned two years later due to resource guarding issues. When Olive arrived we withheld all treats and toys and set new feeding rules for her. After working very hard to improve her manners, Olive now eats from a bowl nicely and does not react when the bowl is taken away.
Best suited in a home with adults only and no cats please.

Smart and Sassy!!  Who doesn’t love and respect a girl who knows what she wants and is not afraid to ask for it?   Olive is all of this and so much more!!   This solid framed, sleek jacketed lady is pure joy to watch as she runs like the wind in one of our fenced in areas!  Paying no attention to the toys scattered about hoping to be activated,  Olive is much more interested in being near her person and in particular getting much needed and yes, deserved belly rubs!  This super sweet, sensitive lady will be at her best in a home with structure and steady routine headed up by humans with prior dog experience.   She enjoys the company of other dogs and in fact, she will tell you her best friend here at the Sanctuary is another pointer, Polly who will oftentimes join her for a brisk walk through some of our wooded trails.  Exploring the sights, sounds and smells of the woods is a favorite past time of Olive along with the reward of yummy snacks at the end of her walk.  Olive is boldly smart and graced with a delightful personality.   She is happiest when she is confident that her humans have everything under control and she need not worry or fret!  Exercise should play a regular role in her daily routine.   Structure, routine and a healthy heap of human love will bring out the very best of Olive.   She’s hoping that soon you will come on by and ask for the ultimate relish, Olive!

animal.description:
Helloooooooo!! My name is Smoke. My foster mom likes to make up songs about me, and sometimes she calls me Smokey, Smokey Bones and Smokestack.

Life for me hasn't always been great.....

My last person kept me chained on a very short chain in the kitchen or crated, unless they wanted to use me for a stud dog. Then, they stopped feeding me. I don't really know don't know why they did that to me.
One day a lady calling herself a Guardian came and took me on a car ride. My owner told the Guardian that the neighbor had poisoned me, so they took me to the doctor. I was so happy to break free from those chains. Truth is, I just needed food, and love.

The next day, I met my foster mom. Although she loves me very much, she tells me that I can't stay with her forever. She promised me that she would love me until my new person finds me.   I have never really had the opportunity to be a puppy, so now.....I am making up for lost time.

I loved the kids (3yrs & 11 yrs) in my first foster home, but I I'm going to need some time and patience so a home with older kids would be best. My biggest downfall is that I just get too excited and want to jump and get wild sometimes.

I need a patient person/family that can give me lots of exercise and is willing to set boundaries and continue to work on my manners. I'm a big boy and I like to go full speed.   I am not a fan of smaller animals, like cats. They look like toys, but they don't like when I play with them. I like some other medium to large easy going dogs but would require a slow introduction.

PROFILE
NAME: Bo
GENDER: Male
DOB (Approx): 08/08/2017
BREED: American Bulldog X

BEHAVIOR
DOGS: Some
CATS: No
KIDS: Older Kids
TRAINING: Housebroken
REQUIREMENTS: Fenced yard

A BIT ABOUT ME

Say hello to the ridiculously handsome Bo. Bo isn't short for anything; he is just THAT cool. 

After spending time with the amazing folks at Walden Way, Bo was recently taken by a loving foster family where he has continued to prosper and developed trust. Bo is currently living with a mature dog with a calm demeanor who has been an excellent role model for him.  He is learning to share his bed and toys with her and follows her lead on walks.  He still needs reminders to not react to other dogs on walks, but has shown incredible improvement! Bo is learning to trust new people and he's doing much better now when visitors drop by the house.

Bo loves the water and spends a lot of time playing with his ball in the kiddie pool and loves to play fetch in the backyard.  Bo also enjoys relaxing especially when he is cuddling with his favorite 8-year-old human!

-----------------------

animal.description:
Kahlua is a 5 year old female Pug & English Bulldog Mix rescued from the shelter. She is a very sweet and playful girl. However, needs to be an only dog. Playful and Energetic. Sweet and Loving. She crates well but howls briefly. Loves toys but needs durable toys as the stuffed ones don’t last long. She sleeps in her little pink bed (she loves it) on a bed. Loves all people. She is part Bulldog so very strong. 

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA. 

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description:
Remington - Doberman/Swissy Mix - Male - 2 years - www.twyla.org

If you'd like to know more about this dog please visit our website at www.Twyla.org

Remington is an energetic 2-year-old Greater Swiss Mountain dog/Doberman mix (we think) who likes to play with toys and other dogs. His previous placement was not working out as he was more dog than the family and resident dog were able to handle. Remington is active and energetic, loves to play ball, is house and crate trained and walks well on leash. He is very smart, learns quickly and wants to please.

Remington is looking for a dog-experienced home that can give him the guidance, training and exercise he needs and craves. He likes playing with other dogs, but has to be reminded not to guard his resources, like toys and food. He LOVES people, walks well on leash and runs nicely next to a bike for exercise. He likes to follow his person throughout the house to make sure he's not missing anything, especially in the kitchen - he loves Ice cubes! 

As he's a large and somewhat pushy character, he's looking for an large-breed experienced home, with or without a similar sized balanced dog. He takes direction well and is fully crate and house trained. 

***Please note: All dogs are fostered in private homes of volunteers, so to meet a dog please fill out an Adoption Application on our website (http://www.twyla.org/adopt/our-adoption-process) so we may setup a private meetup with the dog or coordinate for an Introduction at the next general Adoption Meet  and Greet (as listed on our website: (http://www.twyla.org/upcoming-events), as not all dogs attend all Meet and Greets***
