animal.description:
Snowflake is a loveable and affectionate girl who is a total house dog, just wanting to be inside with her family as a companion and protecter. She is a happy girl with a tail that curls prettily over her back and wags happily when she sees her person, a leash or food bowl. She loves morning and evening walks. She gets along with other dogs and can be bouncy and playful with them but would be content as either an only dog or with another dog her own size. She is house trained, crate trained and respectful of property. She is very mellow overall but can get crotchety with young dogs who are disrespectful. She knows her basic commands and walks well on leash with a training collar. Snowflake loves playing in the yard, car rides and running errands with her person. She is a perfect companion dog who is non-intrusive when you are busy. She has not been around children so would do best in an adult home without cats.

animal.description:
Hello!! My name is Victor!!! My former owner tied me to a pole and abandoned me!!! You can't imagine how scared and alone I felt!!  I was lucky enough to be rescued by these nice people before something bad happened to me!!  
 Even with all that I have been through... I am a very sweet boy that loves attention.  I love to play tug of war, but sometimes I think the leash is a rope toy to tug on, so they are working with me on that.  I take treats very nicely and listen pretty good. 
I do have a very high prey drive and need to work on my listening skills when I see those little critters running or flying around in the yard or when on walks.  I REALLY just want to chase them!! But with consistent training and treats... I'm sure I will learn!! 
I  need someone that is willing to work with me and give me some strict obedience training.  I am a good boy... I just need someone to give me a chance!!  Could you be that someone???
Oh... I almost forgot...  I do not do well with other dogs, so I need to be the only dog in the home and I'm not sure if I have ever been around those little furry things you all call cats!! 
I would love to find my forever home soon.... I have been here far too long.
 I can even be fostered or fostered to adopt!!!
If you can open your heart and home to me... please fill out an adoption application at: 
                                        www.dawghous.com
Thank You! 
Love Victor

Kuma is good with other dogs, and loves kids.  He is a protective dog, so will need dog savvy owners willing to work with him and not allow him to interact with strangers.  He needs slow meet and greets and will never be a dog park dog or one that hangs out at a backyard bbq!

Kuma is totally housebroken, great in his crate, and knows basic commands.  While he is a fetch addict and will require daily exercise, he loves curling up on the couch for movie night and sleeping in in bed on the weekends!

animal.description:
MOLLY NEEDS TO BE THE ONLY DOG IN THE HOME.

MOLLY is a beautiful, 3-year-old, 40-pound Terrier mix with a jolly dog grin and the most outrageous set of ears! How can anyone not fall in love with those ears alone, so goofy! And she has a sweet & silly personality to match. MOLLY likes people & is the perfect size,(approximately 40-pounds). She came to Animal Alliance in January 2018 with her three adorable puppies who have all found their forever homes! It wasn't until just recently that MOLLY was lucky enough to find her own foster home, prior to that she was at our shelter. MOLLY is learning house skills and manners and is eager to please! She loves to play fetch and is happiest when she can cuddle up on the couch with her humans! *** WHAT'S NEXT? If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY! Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date! *** This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives. Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details. To fill out an adoption application, go to: https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

I have been in boarding for a long time, I would love to have my own comfy bed and a family to call my own. I would need a strong person, and someone who is just as stubborn or more so, than me, as I need my training to continue, if you don't remind me, then I will forget, and then I will get in trouble, as I will revert back to my puppy ways of jumping on people, and they say that is not cool. I am Kennedy and I am about 8 years young. I have been waiting for more than 4 years for somebody to adopt me. I was on the list to be euthanized at a high kill shelter, but was saved. Right now I live in a boarding facility and I wish every day for a forever home or at least a foster home. I am sweet and very handsome, as you can see. I love long walks and back yard play. I love to be by your side at all times. I play a little hard to get, but once I warm up, I am all yours. I just need my own special someone to work with me every day. I need strong leadership and someone who will follow through with my training, because if you don't remind me I will forget, then I will go back to my puppy ways of jumping! And people say that is not cool. I dream for a quiet environment with no children where I can be the only pet- I would do best in a home with no other dogs or cats. 

My adoption fee is only $150 and it includes spay/neuter, rabies vaccine, DHPP, and microchip. You can fill out an application at www.pawprinthearts.com and then meet me to see for yourself how awesome I am.

animal.description:
To access the home page for our group, click on Southern Comfort Maltese Rescue which will take you to the map page.  Below the map is our logo and the link to click on to access adoption forms, contact info or to donate. ALL DONATIONS ARE TAX DEDUCTIBLE.


Adoption Fee:  $150.00

Buster is a very sweet, fun and loving fella.  We really don't know how old he is.  The shelter he came from said "age unknown" and followed that up with a guess of 15 years.  Well he is still running and playing with the other dogs two years later, so we just don't believe that!  He weighs around 12 pounds.  
Buster has a peach of a personality and is so precious! He has lots of energy and is always ready to entertain. 
He is not fully house trained.  He will go outside if taken out frequently but will have accidents inside.  He also is a barker, so if that would be a concern for neighbors, then he would not be the right fit.
 
Buster has Cushings disease and a collapsing trachea.  It's a toss up which of those conditions is responsible for his almost constant coughing and he is on six medications daily.  One of those is cough syrup which helps him only temporarily.  Help with his medical costs would be greatly appreciated.  
 
He's doing great in spite of his challenges....always happy and always a great big goofy grin!  
 
Buster is being fostered in Largo, FL enjoying the sun and fun until his forever family picks him up!


NOTE: SCMR DOES NOT adopt to homes with children under the age of 10 years or homes with Electric Fences

Out-of-state adoptions are possible; however, the approved adoptive home is responsible for making the necessary arrangements to pick up their new little one.

Notes: Requires a fenced-in yard with no other dogs or cats.  He has a strong prey drive and needs an experienced handler. 


King is a special boy who needs some special attention. He's a very active, hyper guy, and as such, would not be a good fit for a family with kids. He receives regular training in the shelter with wonderful results, but he definitely needs someone to show him that humans can be trusted and lead him into being the great guy he is in his soul. He's mischievous, rambunctious, willful, loving and smart.

King would do best in a home with moderate to high energy, no dogs or cats, and no children. We think he would be a prime candidate for agility training, a bike rider, or runner. A fenced-in yard is required for King.

If you are interested in adopting this animal please go here to find out how and fill out our app online: http://www.caaws.org/adoption-application/

Adoption Information:  Our dog and cat adoptions are held every Saturday from 11:00am to 3:00pm at our building, located at 6357 Quinn Dr in Baton Rouge, LA, near the Old Jefferson and Tiger Bend intersection. Please see http://caaws.org/special_events.htm to see specific details on which locations we will be at on specific dates. The adoption fee for our animals is $125 and covers all vetting, shots, vaccinations, tests, and neuter/spays.  For further questions please email us at caawsmail@yahoo.com or ask the adoption counselors at adoptions!.

animal.description:
Matilda has an adorable underbite that gives her face such character.  She likes to romp in the yard and also play with a ball.  Matilda can be cautious meeting new people at first, but once she trusts you she is loving, sweet, will give kisses, be silly and happy go lucky.   She is looking for a low foot traffic & quieter home and someone  who is willing to give her some time to get to know them. Matilda is not a fan of cats and at times is picky about her doggie friends. She had tested positive for heartworm but has long since completed heartworm treatment and is doing fine.  Matilda is 5 years old and 68 pounds. Please help Matilda find the loving home she deserves.

Matilda would do best in a home with the following criteria:
-No kids, other dogs/cats/pets
-Adult only household preferred 
-Experienced dog owner
-Low foot traffic home (non active home without lots of people coming in and out)
 
Please understand that we are an animal shelter and thus unable to say whether the dogs are housebroken as they are not in homes.

PLEASE USE THIS LINK TO SUBMIT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION. WE ONLY ACCEPT ADOPTION APPLICATIONS THROUGH OUR WEBSITE. ANY OTHERS WILL NOT BE PROCESSED. Application link here: http://www.oscaranimalrescue.org/oscar-1-application.html

Adoption Process: 
1.Fill out an application

Matilda's adoption fee is $100. This covers all age-appropriate shots, vetting & microchipping.

animal.description:
Please read his full bio on our site before contacting us
comes with DNA test which will be up on our site soon
He's a Catahoula, Beagle, Golden Retriever
Catahoula colors
Beagle body and cuteness
Goldens gentle loving temperament

Located in Redding ca
Approved matching adopter picks up in Redding
See adoption process at
www.sadt.info 



Mikey is the cutest loveliest little guy
about 45 pounds healthy and happy with a small narrow head not big or blocks as some of the pics may look as they are close ups
He looks like a boxer mix and his personality and energy level show that

He's around 6.5 years young and fully house trained, leash trained, knows some commands and listens well 
Once bonded he can easily hike off leash 

Great traveler in car,
Loads up easily 
greets all people in a friendly manner
 a tail wag and smile

You can see him play with a ball in his videos very cute and comical 
He's currently fostered in a home in the mountains of Shasta county
He lives with 6 other dogs ages 5 years to 14 years, sizes 65 to 130 pounds
Males and females
He's fine with all of them and has met other strange dogs of all sizes ages etc
He's great with all friendly and playful dogs or the mellow ones
but if there's an aggressive dog he will stand up for himself
so best to stay away from those
He also does not like to share his ball food or treats with other dogs as he lives as only dog
until now so we like to keep him that way
that's what he prefers as well
he's not needy but into people and likes to be attached to his owner
he likes to follow you around until you throw the ball then goes exploring a bit but never far
comes back more ball play but we don't throw it too far or too often specially on warmer days
and there's always lots of water and baby pools to cool off in
which he does he lays in it until cool then gets out

he likes to just hang out maybe sun himself being near you or not too far away

he has no problems being left for a few hours once he's bonded and feels at home but not looking for anyone that's gone a lot
no daily going to work
looking for a younger tortured couple or person that wants a new family member
not just a dog
he's fine being a home body if there's property and go for a walk on the property or help with chores
so we would love him to go on a small ranch but for the perfect match a large yard will do
 
Mikey is looking for
Someone that is lonely and wants to have lots of love and give the same back to him
Someone healthy enough who will outlive a dog his age
We don't want him to loose another person he so loved
Mikey hospiced his prev. Owner until a week before the end

Now it's Mikey s time to live life to the fullest and have his huge personality shine
in an adult home thats what he's used too
no apartments or trailer parks and a fenced yard
homeowners over the age of 28 years that are stable

Mikey loves to lay next to you on the couch watching football etc
super easy going
he's used to having someone home at all times
but once a week fosters leave and he's alone 7 hours
he's fine with that as long as it's not daily
he is fine inside the house at that time too and it's saver there then in a yard
he loves it cool with the air on goes out a bit to sun bath
he's a morning dog loves to go for a game of ball while you sit and drink your coffee throw his ball
not far maybe at most 20 feet a couple times
since he has to run up and down the steep hills at the foster
he will not stop and keep going so fosters stop so he can just carry his ball around
He loves to collect tons of rawhides and also chew on them in the evening

Once we get your app and you are fully approved as a possible match you can have any and all your questions answered by the foster person before we go on to the meeting which takes place here in Redding California 
Usually it's only one meeting if all goes great as planned you take this cutie home the same day

We are looking for someone that truly knows how to bond with their dog for life

Where it's not just a dog but a best friend 

He does not have any health problems that we're aware off

animal.description:
Max B. is a gorgeous boy who appears to be a mix of black lab and maybe golden retriever. His estimated birthday is April 2013 and he weighs around 75 handsome pounds.

Max made his way to STAF when his owners realized that they were getting old and no longer able to give him the exercise that he needs. Sadly they never explored positive based training for Max. Max had lived with another dog (as well as a cat) in this home and they got along very well, but we believe Max will be happiest being the only dog in a home.

With the lack of exercise and training, Max began pulling more on leash and depending on the dog he was passing, was also becoming more reactive when seeing some dogs while out on a walk. We are quite certain that Max would have benefited greatly from positive based basic obedience while in this home. Max walks very well on leash and is a favorite to walk with many of the STAF volunteers. Max is super smart and already knows many basic commands. He is definitely a pleaser and is eager to learn.

Max is very affectionate and he melts whenever his favorite volunteers make his way.  Sadly Max does have some fears and he does like to take his time getting to know new friends and will do best in a family without younger children as well as a family that would be open to working with STAF’s training team to give Max the best possible fresh start in a new home
 
Max makes regular home visits with a STAF volunteer who let us know that “Max B. is beautiful in my home. House broken, doesn’t touch a thing and is happy to quietly sit by my side all day as I work. He is perfect!"

Max is not a match for the couch potato home, don’t get us wrong he loves to lounge; especially after a long walk or a long fetch match in the yard:).  An active home committed to exercise and positive training will reap the unwavering love and devotion of one very special canine friend.

Max will benefit from: A fenced yard and an active home
Max would love: Positive based training

Please see our homepage for visiting hours and adoption details. 

* All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
* We do not do same-day adoptions; we ask that you return for a follow-up visit before taking an animal home.
* You must be 21 years or older to adopt a dog from STAF
* We require a physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11.  We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog's behavior and exercise needs.
* Invisible fences - Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we cannot adopt to homes with invisible fences.
* We do request vet and personal references.
* At this time, we are only able to consider applicants within 75 miles of Cincinnati.

Can’t adopt but want to help? You can make a difference! Our shelter is run entirely on volunteer-power and generous donations from animal-lovers like you. 100% of your contribution goes directly to caring for our 500+ furry residents.  Thank you for your support.

animal.description:
Jackson - in Maine - updated November 2020

Jackson is a beautiful 3 year old boy and he has had a long rescue journey. He is a handsome big boy who needs a very patient and understanding family who is ready to work with the shyest of boys. Jackson would not do well in an environment with small children or a lot of people coming and going. He definitely does best in the presence of another dog and a consistent routine.  He is very sweet once he gets to know you. He loves to play with toys and run around outside. He doesn't mind cats and he is friendly with every dog he has met.   He is staying with our rehabilitation friends at Kompletely K9 and he helps with some of the other dogs who need a good playmate. 
 
Way back in 2017 the J pups and their mom were found by a mailman out in a rural part of Arkansas. They were in rough shape, living in the summer heat without shelter or shade. Our partner rescuers worked very hard to catch them, nurse them to health and get them ready to journey north. Because the pups were older when rescued, they missed out on critical socialization and it has taken a long time for every one of them to feel safe with people. Because people can be wonderful, all his siblings have found forever homes but Jackson has been a more difficult placement and is working with our friends at Kompletely K9 Training and Rehabilitation.  We just love this big guy and would love to see him find forever love. This is not a dog for first-time owners or for a growing busy family, but for someone with experience with scared dogs. We will work with you on training and slow transition to your home if you have interest in Jackson. 
 
If you have interest in meeting Jackson or any of our cuties, please fill out the adoption application here: http://www.luckypuprescue.org/adoption-application.

Please note: we do not have a physical facility where our dogs are housed; they are cared for in our wonderful foster network throughout New England. It is our expectation that, once approved, a potential family will meet the dog(s) in the foster setting where they are feeling safe and loved.

Thank you for considering rescue!

animal.description:
•Lab/terrier? mix,
•female,
•6 years,
•50 lbs.


Adults only

RURAL SETTING WITH PHYSICAL FENCED YARD

While her looks suggest she might be a chocolate lab mix, her personality is more like a regal old soul,   she just doesn’t quite fit the goofiness associated with that breed, and we debate her heritage regularly. Is she a Chesapeake Bay retriever mix?  A terrier mix? Is she a cat trapped in a dog’s body? We only know Nika is a beautiful, independent girl who takes her time to get to know new people, but once you are in her circle you can see how special she is.

Nika has been with us for a while because she is a true unique spirit, and we know she is just waiting for that perfect home and that we just have to be a bit more proactive in finding it. She is smart and cautious, although roast beef goes a long way in helping her make new friends. Nika can be nervous meeting new people, which has made it a challenge to find her a home, as she does not connect with people until she trusts them, so she needs someone who will take that time and appreciate that her affection is not easily won. 

Nika likes to do her own thing, sniff the yard, play with a toy, but when she is in the mood she loves a good ear scratch or butt scratch.


If Nika could pick her perfect home we suspect she would pick a quiet one, one set far back from the hustle and the bustle, near woods for quiet walks, and maybe with a pond so she can swim (she loves to swim).

An adult or two to love her, and take her for walks, and with a nice fenced-in yard for her to explore and sniff and enjoy. 

Nika was returned to us because the children in the home brought energy and activity that made her nervous, so we would like to see her in an ADULT ONLY HOME. She can also get overwhelmed with a lot of activity outside the home so a busy neighborhood with lots of kids and dogs around can be too much for her; she thrives in a rural setting.

Nika does fine being crated for a work day and seems to enjoy the time to nap, chew her chews, and reflect on life.  She is also house trained, and has good house manners. Once she is used to her person, she comes when called off-leash.

 In the past Nika has lived with a male dog and cats, but we are not sure if she wants to continue sharing her home. As she has matured she may prefer to be the queen of all she surveys, but she may do well with the right dog. We are not sure. We are sure, though, that with love and consistency, Nika is able to relax and be such a wonderful dog, who will make someone very, very happy.

*****
Due to Massachusetts State Regulations we are unable to adopt to residents of Massachusetts at this time. We apologize for any inconvenience.
*****
 If you are interested in adopting this dog, please complete an adoption application at https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/PEP/Dog. Or visit our site (http://peppertree.org/adoptlist.php) and learn about other Peppertree dogs. *Note: visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Ziggy is a giant ball of fun whose love for people is only exceeded by his love for giving kisses. A very tall Boxer mix, he is as handsome as he is confident and smart. Ziggy is eager to please and as happy to be playing fetch as he is with just sitting next to you with his chew toy. We know he will make any home feel complete, not just with his sheer size but with his sheer love too. 

Ziggy has every reason to dislike people instead of loving them. He was adopted as a puppy and dumped in a Utah shelter. We immediately flew him home and were shocked at his transformation. This handsome dude had received zero socialization and manners. Ziggys intelligence is evidenced by his recent graduation from a 6 week board and train program with Golden Heart Canine. Here Ziggy learned basic commands and how to better interact with other dogs. 

Ziggy is almost a perfect gentleman on the leash. He knows heel, sit, stay, and wait. He is still working on his doggie interactions and proper introductions, but you can tell he wants to do the right thing! His forever home will need to continue his training, recognize his areas of improvement, and love the goofball that he is. Ziggy relies on his human to perform proper introductions and be the alpha, therefore, he would do best with an experienced owner or breed experience. To help with this the rescue will provide support from the trainers along with videos showing the techniques that need to be continually practiced For now, Ziggy would do best as an only dog in the home and preferably should not be in a home with small children. Ziggy is crate trained, potty trained, and is a great kisser! 

We know Ziggy's REAL forever home is out there, waiting to spoil this love bug with kisses, treats, and continued training! So why wait for Valentine's Day to meet this hunk when he's available to sweep you off your feet now!

*BSL Restrictions may apply.

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	3 Puppy combo shots (Distemper/Parvo)
	Bordetella
	Micro-chip
	Rabies
	De-worming

animal.description:
"BE SURE TO WATCH MY VIDEO!" 

LINCOLN IS IN A FOSTER HOME

Date of birth: 11/2016

1/27/2021: Lincoln is a playful and fun-loving Hound/Malamute mix! He’s 4 years old and weighs 70 lbs. Lincoln is very friendly and he's a total ham! He absolutely loves to play with tennis balls and toys. He loves to fetch and he can also entertain himself with his toys. 

• Lincoln is looking for a home with someone who has dog experience and a fenced yard to play fetch in.  He loves playing outdoors, but he needs a privacy fence— he will jump a short fence. 

• He needs daily exercise to wear him out. He really enjoys going for walks and he walks nicely on a leash. He loves to take in all the smells! 

• Lincoln is a bit too rambunctious to live in a home with young kids, and he needs a home without other dogs or cats. Fortunately, he's got enough personality to fill a home all on his own! He's a character and makes us laugh a lot! 

• He is house trained and crate trained.  He’s not a big fan of the crate, but his foster parents say that he isn’t destructive when left uncrated.

• He is very food motivated and he loves treats! 

• His foster parents describe him as equally snuggly and independent. He’s a big lap dog, but also happy to curl up by himself. 

• He can walk in pack walks near other dogs and is not reactive. 

• He knows several commands— sit, down, leave it, and down… although sometimes he conveniently forgets!  

• He’s not a big barker. He’ll bark when the mail comes or when someone knocks, but not excessively at all.

• Lincoln has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms. He was a stray. He’ll be a great companion for someone looking for a goofy, fun-loving guy! 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE: PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU. Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.  

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Phone: 913.596.1000 ext. 113

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Personality:

None of our foster dogs are tested with cats because we have no way of testing them with cats. Siberians are notorious for their high prey drive and typically kill cats, rabbits, chickens, birds, squirrels, opossums, etc., so we we don't have much success adopting them out to homes with cats. Most of our foster dogs are with us for killing cats, chickens and goats to begin with so our assumption is they are not good with cats and other small things that move.

Siberians are typically good with children of all ages and the only reason we would not list them as not good with kids is because they may be too energetic and bouncy and knock over a toddler.

Southern Siberian Rescue is a volunteer based 501(c)3 organization based out of Raleigh, NC, so we do not have a physical facility with operating hours that you can visit to meet our dogs. All of our foster dogs are in our personal homes. You need to fill out our adoption application (http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption) and get approved to adopt and then we will set a time for you to meet our foster dogs. As a volunteer based group, we all have jobs, family, personal dogs and other commitments but we try to acknowledge and process applications as quickly as we can. That being said, we try to keep our available foster dogs as current as we can also but it is time consuming to get pics and information on new dogs so not all of our dogs are listed at all times. Please fill out our application and then we can discuss dogs that will work for you and your situation. We average 40-45 Siberians in our program so we are certain we have one that will work for you. Please know that we are not obligated to answer inquiries on dogs as we will focus on approved applicants. Again, there is ample time to discuss all of our foster dogs AFTER we have an approved application on file. We do adopt out of state as long as we can get a home check done. We ask that you, your family and existing pets make the trip to NC to meet and adopt our foster dogs.

SSR can not and will not hold dogs for anyone. If we do, that means another Siberian will die in a shelter because a shelter dogs time is very limited, as is our foster space. We do our best to process applications in the order received and first application gets first interest in our foster dog(s). We understand that there will be scheduling conflicts with home checks and meet and greets but we will try to accommodate for that if a potential adopter has interest in a particular foster dog in our program.

All Southern Siberian Rescue foster dogs are microchipped, up to date on shots, spay/neutered, on monthly heartworm preventative and flea and tick preventative. For additional information on Southern Siberian Rescue and Siberian Huskies, please visit www.SouthernSiberian.com. To fill out an application, please visit

http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption
.

animal.description:
Ziggy is a giant ball of fun whose love for people is only exceeded by his love for giving kisses. A very tall Boxer mix, he is as handsome as he is confident and smart. Ziggy is eager to please and as happy to be playing fetch as he is with just sitting next to you with his chew toy. We know he will make any home feel complete, not just with his sheer size but with his sheer love too. 

Ziggy has every reason to dislike people instead of loving them. He was adopted as a puppy and dumped in a Utah shelter. We immediately flew him home and were shocked at his transformation. This handsome dude had received zero socialization and manners. Ziggys intelligence is evidenced by his recent graduation from a 6 week board and train program with Golden Heart Canine. Here Ziggy learned basic commands and how to better interact with other dogs. 

Ziggy is almost a perfect gentleman on the leash. He knows heel, sit, stay, and wait. He is still working on his doggie interactions and proper introductions, but you can tell he wants to do the right thing! His forever home will need to continue his training, recognize his areas of improvement, and love the goofball that he is. Ziggy relies on his human to perform proper introductions and be the alpha, therefore, he would do best with an experienced owner or breed experience. To help with this the rescue will provide support from the trainers along with videos showing the techniques that need to be continually practiced For now, Ziggy would do best as an only dog in the home and preferably should not be in a home with small children. Ziggy is crate trained, potty trained, and is a great kisser! 

We know Ziggy's REAL forever home is out there, waiting to spoil this love bug with kisses, treats, and continued training! So why wait for Valentine's Day to meet this hunk when he's available to sweep you off your feet now!

*BSL Restrictions may apply.

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	3 Puppy combo shots (Distemper/Parvo)
	Bordetella
	Micro-chip
	Rabies
	De-worming

This injury does not cause him any pain and the vet suggested to just leave it as is since it is not causing any problems. August would do best in a home with no other pets. 

Auggie does not like some dogs so he does not do well going out for walks. He will growl like he is going to attack but it is all growl and no bite. He is quite the couch potato but makes a wonderful companion for someone looking for a pal.

The ideal home for Auggie is a home with a fenced yard and a comfy bed. 

If you think you can give this boy a loving home to live out his years, please fill out our online application at www.dogsinneedorg.com.

animal.description:
***STL Foster Needed***

Blaze, 4yrs, Male, Staffie mix, Black with white, 50lbs

Blaze is a sweet boy he knows you and is often aloof around strangers. Blaze was adopted from us back in 2014 when he was just 4 months old. He lived happily with his family and even welcomed their new baby into the home the following year. Unfortunately, the child was diagnosed with autism and the energy level and sound made Blaze very uncomfortable in his home. He started hiding on a regular basis, so for safety concerns for all involved he came back to rescue.

Blaze was an only dog in the home and after his adoption did not socialize with other dogs, it is still unclear if he is willing to accept other dogs. Though dogs he has become familiar with he will wag his tail and play bow at the kennel and through the fence. Once there is direct contact, he loses his confidence and shuts down and sometimes acts defensive. So we are still working on his confidence building around other dogs. He has not been cat tested. 

Due to his experience is his past home we feel it is best for Blaze to not be placed in a home with young children.

Blaze can be shy of new people, but once he warms up he is an absolute love. He loves hanging out with his humans and doing whatever they are doing. 

Blaze is crate trained and has good house manners.

We are also looking for a foster home that would be able to further work with Blaze while he awaits his forever home. The foster home would have to have the ability to keep him separate from the other animals in the home and follow instructions given b y the rescue for training and socialization. 

Foster or adopter must be local to the Saint Charles County, MO metro area.

Blaze's adoption fee is $200.00 and he is fully vetted. Interested adopters or foster must submit an application through our website to be considered.

animal.description: Jarod was abandoned at a local Alabama veterinary office and as they opened the clinic one morning, they found this young puppy tied to their front door. A local Humane Association took this adorable baby and jokingly named him Jarod after the vet, Jarod Grantland.  As little Jarod grew, they soon realized what an enormous energy level he had. He jumps so high that he literally back flips back down to the floor. Jarod is extremely smart and is always trying to figure ways of getting out of being a good dog and running around driving us crazy.  He does this on purpose.....he is a smart dog.  One day I decided to challenge him and in a matter of 30 minutes, he learned “sit”, “shake”, “high 5” and “double high 5”.  He is the best dog in their humane shelter on feeding manners. He will sit and stare at his bowl forever until the command to eat is given. He will even shake your hand before eating to show his gratitude.  On that note, he is the worst dog in our shelter as far as being a curious brat! Turn your back for one second and he has opened every door or gate and proudly running amuck to show you what he did...lol. Jarod needs an experienced owner to control his mischievous ways. We also DNA tested him just for fun. Jarod is so slim and long legged that we were really betting on Greyhound.  He is 50% Staffordshire, 25% Boxer and 25% Hound/Terrier Group. Jarod is now 4 years old and has been with them since around 4 months old.  If ever there was a sad situation for a brilliant dog who deserves a real home, it is Jarod.  This heartbreaking situation just cannot continue in his life.  It breaks our heart and no telling how he really feels year after year not having the comforts of a real home. He lives in a kennel with a nice bed and good food....but not a home.  We will really  scrutinize where this boy goes.... we truly will.  We don't want a failure or return. He needs someone that loves a challenge and energy and intelligence that could outsmart you on a day you let your guard down.  But then again.... we don't really know what Jarod would do if he was the center of some family's world.  Would the antics stop?  And then would he just say....let's learn and be a great team and family?    Maybe Jarod needs to be a service dog that tracks things down or finds lost people?   Truly this boy is an Einstein trapped in a beautiful dog's body.  Does anyone have the key to unlock this boy from his kennel and let him REALLY live a good life where he can max out his potential?????  If you are so inclined to toss your hat into this adoption ring for Jarod...please email us at peaceloveandanimals@gmail.com. We are praying that we can change the stalemate in Jarod's life very soon.

Bishop, 4yrs, Male, Cane Corso mix, blue brindle, 70lbs

Bishop is a very regal kind of guy who adores his humans. He is the type of dog that can see into your soul, so if you have bad intentions you are best to steer clear.

Bishop is a happy pup who enjoys doing what his humans are doing. Want to go for a run or hike? Bishop is down. Want to curl up and cuddle with a good movie? Bishop is down. Want to go on a road trip? Bishop is down.

Bishop does well with medium and up even tempered well balanced dogs. Small dogs and cats are a no go for him. Bishop needs a yard with a 6 foot privacy fence to keep him safe.

Though he is smaller in stature than a full blooded Corso, his personality is all Corso. Bishop will be protective of his home and people and needs a structured home with prior guardian breed experience.

Bishop has good house manners and is crate trained. Though he has been around a small child in his foster home, due to his protective nature he would do best in a home with older or no kids.

Bishop is a local Saint Charles County, MO metro area only adoption.

Bishops adoption fee is 350.00 and he is fully vetted. Interested adopters need to submit an adoption application through our website, steppingstonebully.org to be considered.

animal.description:
Koda was born on 4/16/14. He is Pit Bull mix. He is neutered, microchipped, and has been vaccinated/dewormed/treated for fleas. He is potty trained, crate trained, enjoys car rides and going for walks. He's approx 84lbs - brindle with some white on him.

This dog has been FAILED by his former family and the "trainer(s)" they worked with. When he became too much work - he was scheduled to lose his life. When we reached out to take him/save his life... we had to plead with them to spare this young healthy dogs life. This is not a dog who does not deserve to live. This is not a dog who deserves to die because he's been failed by the very humans who were supposed to love him.

This IS a dog who will require a home who has the time, patients, energy, dedication, and love that will take to form a bond with him. He needs an owner who is not the least bit intimidated by his size or power. He IS stubborn- he needs an owner who won't give in or give up on him!! This isn't a therapy dog, service dog, or emotional support dog.. this is a rescue dog who needs a very committed loving owner who is willing to offer him the loving home he deserves. 

I would like him to be an only pet. While he has lived with other animals and is living with other animals in my home.. due to some small incidents we have had with him and other animals due to jealousy and some resource guarding - we feel he'd be happiest as an "only". He has never lived with children nor has he had much experience with children. He is easily excited and plays ROUGH.. for this reason, he'd do best in an adult only home.

To elaborate on how he plays... his former owners played very rough with him, so he has a hard time containing himself when he thinks its play time... I do NOT recommend rough housing with a dog of his size and power. He needs an owner who can set boundaries so he knows what is acceptable. When he tries to play outside with you - he'll race around and jump all over barking loudly... if you didn't know him, you could think he was being aggressive- but he just wants you to run around and play rough with him... which we do NOT do with him... so he's really catching on that when we're outside playing TOGETHER, it's a nice game of fetch!

We would like his new family to be open to working with a reputable trainer who understands dog behavior. We have a trainer we will recommend who has seen this dog, worked with this dog, and played an important role in saving this dogs life.

While this dog can be a handful... he is not a horrible dog. He is not out of control, and he is VERY deserving of a loving home. I can easily handle him.. and I've been working hard not to put him in situations that would be stressful and I make sure I am always in control of the situation.. this dog needs a strong confident leader, but also someone who will teach him it's okay to love. He still gets excited when he hears cars pull up.. he doesn't understand why his former family gave up on him. He's much more loyal than they ever dreamed of being.. and he's one of the saddest dogs I've met... can you help me remind this guy that not all humans suck?

His dishes, blanket, toys, etc will go with him to his new home. We also have a crate and an outdoor kennel/run that we are happy to send with him to  his new home if needed/wanted.

If he is too active - running, jumping, hiking, etc- he will favor one of his back legs. Ensuring he doesn't over do it with being too active seems to help.

If there is anything else you would like to know please don't hesitate to reach out! If you're interested in becoming this guys new best friend... let's talk!! PLEASE be serious about adoption if you contact me about him. PLEASE be willing to work with a trainer if you're interested in adopting this dog. He will need dedication to get him to understand that not everyone will turn their back on him.

Marysville, WA
425-350-1198
SaraNW113@gmail.com

animal.description:
Meet Buck! Buck is estimated to be about 1 1/2 yrs old with some rough times behind him- obvious from his embedded collar injury and the possible burn scar on his rear leg. Our best guess at breed is a Lab/Hound mix. Buck is 60 lbs of happy energy and he gets along well with other dogs and is potty trained and crate trained. Buck loves to meet new people! His enthusiasm leads him to jump up to greet people so we are working on manners. He would be perfect for an active person and would be a great running partner! He is a very smart dog so he needs to keep his mind stimulated. He has already learned sit and down and we are working on roll over. He is easily motivated so additional training or training classes would be perfect for him! He needs a secure fence and supervision while outside. Because he is a big puppy he would do best in a home with no small kids and other medium to large dogs. While he is good with other dogs he does bark when on a leash at unfamiliar dogs which can sound a little intimidating, but he is just so excited and wants to play. He has a goofy personality. His favorite snack is bananas and he likes to play in the bathtub!

Buck is available for adoption with Saving Grace Dog Rescue of San Antonio. The adoption fee is $150.00. An adoption application, home visit and adoption contract are all required. All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations appropriate for their age, microchipped, and wormed for internal and external parasites. If you would like more information or an adoption application, please email us at sgdrsa@outlook.com.

Please note that visual breed identification in rescue dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only GUESSING at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

This boy was definitely worth the save. He actually acts like a 2-3 year old dog as he loves to run circles in the yard when he gets excited. He is doing well with his leash waling and will even carry it to the door for you when he knows he is going outside! What a smart boy! Grant will do best as the only dog in the house as he becomes very attached to his owner. He loves to hike the trails with his foster dad and loves the outdoors. Grant is great home alone for a few hours and also is good in a crate if you are gone for the day at work. He is a snuggler and would love someone to lay on the couch with. He loves his people! He is pretty good with other dogs but he does take a little time to warm up if they are not laid back like his foster brother Cooper is. Carey Grant takes it slow and easy in determining if a new dog is going to be his buddy. He will chase cats so let's not move him in to a house with any.

animal.description:
**NO PHONE CALLS PLEASE** ... We are so busy with rescuing and caring for animals and can't return everyone's inquiry. If you are interested in adopting this pet...You must fill out the adoption application at:
http://www.marlcares.org/adopt_app-dog.php
PLEASE READ all the following info. We do not reply to inquiries asking if the dog is still available, if it is listed here, then it is still available.

We are looking for a foster home or forever home for K.I.

K.I. was surrendered to us December 2017 after a year of watching him live on a short chain that he was constantly tangled up on.  We met K.I. through our Dog House Project...we were going door to door in a rural area offering dog houses and spay/neuter services to dogs in need and on chains in a rural area and he was in the road dragging a big chain...we stopped and got right in the van with us and immediately started giving us kisses...He had us at hello...The owner wouldn't let us have him, but we visited him often and took supplies and checked on him and continued to offer to take him if they would surrender him to us.  Persistence and patience paid off...it took a year...but they finally surrendered him to us.  He is the sweetest most affectionate dog you will ever meet.  He loves to go for rides.  He was great with all their grandchildren and when they would come visit you would see them walking him.  We were told that he had started out as a house dog when their son first got him...probably as a puppy, but when the son had to move back home, he could not be inside and because he would not stay put...they put him on the chain.  We think he had been on this chain for at least 2 to 3 years.  He is kennel trained and we think his approx age is 4 years old and he weighs 69 lbs as of Dec 2017.  He is a very strong boy and needs an owner that can handle his strength.  All he wants to do is cuddle and get attention.  You can see his heart break when he can't get to someone to be petted.  He is enthusiastic and can be energetic, but settles down very quickly and is calm and laid back and just wants to sit with you as long as you will pet him.  We just got him and will post more details as we get to know them.  We haven't had him long enough to know much about how he is with other dogs.  We do know that he had been loose alot with strays in his area and was ok when we saw him out with them, but since he was living a solitary life on a chain we want to really check this out.  Currently he has met 2 female dogs his size and did fine.  He is heartworm positive and we have started him on the slow kill method of doxy and advantage multi, but will treat him with the fast kill method in few months after he has settled into foster and been on doxy long enough.  We have pics of his life before and how he lived...he doesn't even look like the same dog now ... he smiles and is happy all the time now that he is off that chain.  Everyone at our vet loved him and everyone that meets him is just crazy about him.  You will never meet a dog that has more affection to give than this one.  He is looking for an owner that will be his very best friend forever...a companion to spend his life with.  Please consider K.I. ... he needs you.

Adoption fee is $150 and includes ... spayed/neutered, microchipped, current vaccinations,  and kennel trained.

ADOPTION APPLICATION: If you are interested in this pet you must fill out the Adoption Application…which you can find on this site or you can copy and paste this link … http://www.marlcares.org/adopt_app-dog.php
This does not obligate you in any way. If this does not work for you then you can email us at midsouthpets@aol.com for one.

PLEASE READ about our ADOPTION PROCESS AND REQUIREMENTS provided on this site before contacting us.  You can find it quickly by clicking on our NAME or MORE ABOUT US in the column to the right of this pet’s description.  All your questions can be answered by reading the following info provided below.  Our pets are fostered in the Memphis Area, a tri-state area, TN/AR/MS.  Most are fostered in Red Banks, MS.  

We do not allow meetings with any of our dogs until we have your Adoption Application.  Adopting a new family member should involve a well-thought out and deliberate process. This is not an impulse purchase. Please understand that we do not want these animals to be homeless again. We try to complete the process as quickly as possible and appreciate all the applications and will consider each and every one we receive. 

Filling out the Adoption Application does not obligate you in any way, but simply tells us a little bit about you and whether you and this pet would be a good fit for each other.  We will call you after we receive your application and answer all your questions and talk to you about this pet.  After being approved, we will set up a time to bring the pet to meet you and your family and pets or set up a time for you to meet the pet at the foster home.

NO PHONE CALLS PLEASE.  Rescue is a full time job every day.  Please know because we are so very busy with the dogs along with processing applications, updating webpage’s, rescuing, in many vet appointments, caring for seniors and hospice dogs, etc, etc that we are not able to return phone calls or emails asking if this dog is still adoptable, how much is it to adopt, is it house trained etc…We have included all the info we have on this dog at this current time and update the bio as we learn more about them.  We kennel train all the dogs and will indicate if there are housebreaking issues that we have discovered.  We update our site regularly so if the dog is listed here they are in fact adoptable, but may have applications coming in on them, so if you are interested, you need to get your application in now.

**WE RESERVE THE RIGHT TO REFUSE ANY ADOPTION**  Our first concern is the happiness and welfare of the animal.  We respect our potential adoptors and appreciate your interest in adopting one of our pets.  We care about you too and that you are getting the right fit for your home and lifestyle.  By following our process, together we can make sure you are getting the right pet.**

NOTE: We prefer to adopt in the Mid-South AREA, usually no more than 1-2 hours away in driving distance. It is up to the foster home, how far they are willing to drive. We rarely adopt long distance, but will consider each and every application. 
 
MidSouth Animal Rescue League is an all breed, 501c3, non-profit organization that prefer to rescue senior dogs and special cases.  WE LOVE ROTTWEILERS...With 20 years of experience with our beloved ROTTWEILER breed, and little help for this breed in our area, we try to focus on rescuing them and try not to ever have to turn any away that need us…especially the seniors that end up in shelters.  Currently, we have several senior rottweilers in our hospice foster program.  We always need more fosters so that we never have to say NO to them or other seniors.  

We have also started a community relief effort specifically in the Red Banks, MS area not far from us, called The Dog House Project, where we go door to door providing dog houses to dogs on chains and other dogs and cats without proper shelter, including straw in cold temps, as well as food and other supplies as needed.   We offer free spay/neuter services to those animals and continue to check on them all year.  To date many have been spayed and neutered and some have been surrendered from their neglected lives on chains.  We are making a difference and need your donations to continue this program.  We always need igloo type dog houses.  

MidSouth Animal Rescue League relies on the kindness, generosity, and financial support of people like you so that we can continue to rescue and care for dogs like this one. We are a group of dedicated volunteers who respond to animals in need in shelters, strays, and from individuals. We receive no federal or state funds and are supported solely by private donations. 

Many of the animals we save are in need of special medical care or surgery to bring them back to health before they can be placed. Veterinary care, vaccinations, tests, x-rays, medications, spay and neutering, heartworm prevention, flea/tick prevention, worming, food, kennels, grooming, and other supplies are provided for each dog while in our care.

Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at the dog's predominant breed or breed mix. Our adoption fees vary from $150 and up. All of our dogs are up to date on vaccines, heart worm preventives, and flea/tick medication, and will be spayed/neutered prior to adoption. animal.description:
Nina's history.

As of 8/19/2020, I am sad to report that Nina is no longer available. 

An aggressive form of Melanoma has been diagnosed - 2 biopsies were taken to confirm - and, although the cataracts were the least of her problems (which I had planned to resolve), I cannot do anything to stop the cancer. I have been taking her in weekly for checks and the vet said that when she stops eating and cannot drink - it is time. :(  I'm afraid that time has arrived as of this week. I have tried to feed her by hand but the tumor is growing rapidly and interfering with her ability to eat. I am sorry to report this. I will be removing her from Petfinder by tomorrow (Thursday 8-20-2020.) Thank you all for asking about her. I could not be caring for a sweeter companion.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Nina came to me scared and skinny. She had not had a bath, been groomed, or vaccinated since the day she was adopted in April 2008. The couple lived with his son-in-law and his wife and I am told the dog was never taken for a walk, never saw a vet other than the first time she was adopted, never had a dental and never lived with anyone who showed her any kindness. When I took her in she weighed 10 lb; the son-in-law was planning to have her euthanized until I told him I would take her in. Then he had her shaved down to her bony skin. I was told she is poodle and I think there is poodle in her but her conformation shows Bischon Frise.

She has gone from the scraggy, scared ol' lady to a princess with the energy of a puppy. She greets me standing on her back legs, front legs pawing the air as you see many poodles do. She's a good ol' girl but wants to be the boss of my 75 lb Boxer cross! Yes, she does get away with it. 

Nina has cataracts in both eyes. However, it doesn't slow her down at all. I was told by the Eyecare for Animals that white dogs such as Nina are prone to cataracts. I have an appt to get her cataracts assessed. I did have them assessed - 3500.00 for one eye and 6500.00 for both eyes.  We did have someone from WA state who met her. As it is with many people, sometimes when you see a pet you consider, suddenly it brings back memories of a past loved one. I know that feeling too. Since her teeth needed attention, I got a much needed dental for her - $1800.00  As soon as I can afford to get her eyes done, I will do that too.  Nina gets along great with my other dogs and the cats. One of my other dogs, a Poodle, was diagnosed when he was a year old. At that time I had surgery on both eyes for him. He is now 11. Having eye issues has not slowed Nina down one bit. She runs like a racehorse. She now weighs about 15 or 16 lb. Like I said, she has the energy of a puppy. Older dogs (and cats) are at a disadvantage since the majority of the people  do not want a dog older than a couple of years. Dogs like Nina are marvelous companions. If a senior person wants an pet full of energy, she would be perfect because I know the joy and comfort she can bring into a person's life. Taking her for walks would not be marathon adventure. You don't have to try to keep up with her. She'll keep up with you. If you truly want a loving companion, please consider her.  Since I am unable to upload pictures from my phone to this computer, I would gladly send it to you from my phone. Several people have inquired about her. I believe that in one of the interviews she was just too energetic for the person's lifestyle. She has had a couple of interviews since then. May 31 is the first opportunity that Nina will have to get groomed since this whole COVID situation started and everything was closed down. She is all the characteristics you see. It's so easy to fall in lover with her - at least it is for me.

If you would like to see her or have questions, please feel free to contact me at my gmail address:  KRSDINC@GMAIL.COM. 

Thank you for reading this.

Hi, everyone!  My name is Blake.  I've been at TIRR Rescue since 2017.

I used to be at a shelter with my sister Gwen, but we were diagnosed with distemper.  The shelter just didn't have the resources to treat us, so they sent us to TIRR Rescue in the hopes they could help us get better and find great homes.

I am now completely cured of distemper, as is Gwen.  I could really use a nice, loving home that will give me the love and attention I need.  I can be a little intense at first, but I am a great guy once you get to know me.  I could use some basic obedience training and someone who is willing to be patient with me while I get to know them.  If you think you may be that person, be sure to contact my rescue people!

~~~~

Blake is a wary dog who will need an attentive owner willing to give him time and work with him on obedience.  He loves to run the fence and play in the water but also knows how to chill when it's time to come in.

~~~~

animal.description:
Hey, everyone!  My name is General.  I came to TIRR Rescue from New Jersey back in 2018.

My owners sent me to a trainer who didn't treat me well.  When I came back, I was very fearful and would bite without hesitation or reservation if I thought something was a threat.  I ended up biting someone I thought was trying to hurt me, so my family sent me to TIRR Rescue to find a new forever home.  My rescue people think I'm finally ready to find my someone special.

I get along well with some dogs, especially if they like to run and play!   However, I am very much a house dog; I don't like to spend much time outside, especially in this nasty Texas heat.  I am still very hesitant around new people.  I will need a very experienced owner who understands that I don't like strangers and will need to be monitored whenever someone is around.

If you think you could be my forever family, be sure to contact my rescue people!

~~~~

PERSONALITY:
General will need a very experienced owner with extensive Rhodesian Ridgeback knowledge.  He was treated badly by a trainer, and it left him fearful of new people.  He will need an owner that is willing to set him up for success - meaning no crowds and no visitors without crating him - and work with him through his fears.  He will bite if he perceives a threat and has no other means of escape. While he does have a bite history, he is very sweet and playful with the people he knows well.  Due to his background, only adopters who have previously owned Rhodesian Ridgebacks will be considered.

~~~~

To learn more about General, please visit tirrrescue.org/general.

We have no idea her history, but she has shorter legs, a collie look to her face and markings as well as color. We can only guess she has some Corgi, some Lab, some something else in her genetic pool too.  

What matters is that she is a good gal that deserves a home. She is FREE to a good home.  She deserves a home. 
<_____________________________>

DEE DOLLY DO is estimated d.o.b. 3/30/15.  She was a former stray, found with a younger male pup that was very German Shepherd in appearance. They were found in the Aquilla MO area. 

Dolly is a playful gal, who is kenneled with an active male and female.  They play so well and eat together, no arguments. 

I believe she will be better in a home with medium to large males.  She is a mild alpha, so I would not place her in a home with another female unless your dog is very submissive.  No cats.  She has prey drive.  

We treated her for Heartworms.  She is in great health and is a dog who enjoys being petted..  

This poor gal has been locked in a pen here since 2017.   No interest in her and we are shocked...  Someone please give her a home.  Fenced in yard or a city home where she goes out on a leash.  She is a hunter, and was found as a stray, we think lost after a storm. So she will possibly not be loyal to your property if not contained in a fence or on a leash when out.  

Mature weight should be 40 pounds.  

Adoption fee is $FREE.
 
ALWAYS CALL US or LEAVE YOUR TELE IN THE COMMENTS ASKING FOR MORE INFORMATION ...

To adopt call Marilyn at 573-722-3035 from 9:30am to 9:30pm CENTRAL TIME. Please leave your telephone if you send us a request to adopt so I can contact you! (:>))

We may be able to help with transport. We ship all over the USA. 

You can help us by sharing posts of our dogs on your FB page and by email to friends. 

If you like music, check out our SAXOPHONE CD that is easy listen music that the pets will even like!  Michael Neville donated his CD to help the pets!  Go to our Website to download single songs for $.99 cents each OR download all 13 classic tunes for just $9.99. Simple, fast to do and YOU get something back when you donate to us! 

You can listen to four sample songs at this link:

animal.description:
Tripp is a 5 ½ year old cattle dog/shepherd mix.  He is neutered and current on all vaccinations.  Tripp was rescued from the Navajo nation in New Mexico in August 2017.  He has been in a couple of car accidents and his front leg was amputated.  He also has an old fractured rear leg that he needs to be cautious with.  Because of the way his rear leg has healed and the amputated front leg he has a hop-skip walk.  He needs a calm home with no stairs and carpeting or lots of rugs so he will not slip. Tripp has good house manners and he uses a doggie door.

animal.description:
My name is DUCKY and I'm a handsome 11 mo M White/Black Amstaff/Pitbull X. I'm 55 lbs of SILLY HAPPY GO LUCKY BOY.  I am affectionately named so because I have bent front legs and slightly bowed back legs and the vet says it could be due to being crated as a young puppy for months in a crate that was too small or it could be a genetic condition and I was not given proper nutrition so my bones didn't form properly. Either/or the vet feels that surgery would be too painful and risky at this point. It's ok, my bent legs give me character and a sweet goofy "Charlie Chaplin" walk and I get along just fine. I love to run and play and when I run you can barely notice my bent legs. I'm super fun loving and sweet and friendly to all. I am good with other dogs but I am a little ackward in approach so I tend to scare small dogs a bit but I'm good with other playful young big dogs. I'm a little too interested in cats and will chase them. I think I would be best with older kids ages 10 yrs + and because of my legs it would be best for me to be in a home in the country with a grass yard so I can be on soft surfaces because of my legs. I am a very "SPECIAL" boy in more ways than one and I will unleash my charm on you once you meet me.. so please come meet me today!

For more info/app; please email: CECE@TAILSOFLOVERESCUE.ORG

animal.description:
Cecil was originally found at 9- 10 months old dragging a leash in Carmel, IN. Due to a diligent Good Samaritan, who tried to find his owner, Cecil's history was discovered. He and his littermate were set free as puppies by someone who no longer wanted them. A neighbor fed them on a regular basis, but was not interested in keeping them. His littermate was killed in a coyote trap, and not wanting the same fate for him, gave him to her brother.  Her brother didn't want him either and set him free in Carmel in hopes of finding a home.  He was born in March of 2017. He has displaced aggression, which means when he is riled up about seeing another dog outside his area, he can't get to it, so it bites the thing closest to him,. Walking with a muzzle solves this problem. He loves going for walks, rides well in the car and gets along well with other dogs. We believe he is a Great Pyrenees/Golden Retriever mix. He has double dew claws on his rear legs, and dark eyeliner around his eyes. He has the look of both breeds. Cecil loves to give hugs by leaning on you, but he needs his space when doing his job guarding, and does not like to be manhandled. He currently weighs about 100 lbs. He was adopted for two years, and because of the adopter's incompetence in dealing with displaced aggression, after biting the adopter on a walk, they took him to the vet to be euthanized. Fortunately the vet contacted us, since he was adopted through IGPR, and saved his life by getting him back to us. Cecil will need an experienced adopter who is comfortable dealing with displaced and high value food aggression. He is a smart boy and responds well to training. Due to his rough start in life, we believe he does have some PSTD and reverts back to those protective behaviors when in a challenging situation. He is a sweet boy, who is well behaved in the house.  He does not need to be crated when you are gone.  He does need his space when doing his guarding. 

 He will be placed in an adult only home as an inside pet with access to visible secure fencing, Pyrs  and most pyr mixes do not do well with wireless fencing. 

We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 18 years old. If you are interested in fostering or adopting Cecil, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption. In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

Adoption fee is $350
